# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-at-the-summer-olympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The **1912 Summer Olympics** (Swedish: *Olympiska sommarspelen 1912*), officially known as the **Games of the V Olympiad** (Swedish: *Den V olympiadens spel*) and commonly known as **Stockholm 1912**, were an international multi-sport event held in Stockholm, Sweden, between 6 July and 22 July 1912.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 6 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] They were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1910s as the 1916 Summer Olympics in Berlin were cancelled due to World War I.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations and 2,408 competitors, including 48 women, competed in 102 events in 14 sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of tennis (starting on 5 May) and football and shooting (both starting on 29 June), the games were held within a month with an official opening on 6 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was the last Olympics to issue solid gold medals and, with Japan's debut, the first time an official team from an Asian nation participated.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm was the only bid for the games, and was selected in 1909.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The games were the first to have art competitions, women's diving, women's swimming, and the first to feature both the decathlon and the new pentathlon, both won by the American Jim Thorpe.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Electric timing was introduced in athletics, while the host country disallowed boxing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Figure skating was rejected by the organizers because they wanted to promote the Nordic Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (26), while hosts Sweden won the most medals overall (65).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games for eight years due to the disruption of the First World War.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1920 in Antwerp.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Following the 1908 Summer Olympics in London, authorities in Sweden immediately sought to ensure that the next games would be held there.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were two Swedish members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) at the time, Viktor Balck and Clarence von Rosen.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The pair proposed the idea to the Swedish governing bodies of athletics and gymnastics in order to ensure that they backed any potential bid.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Support was given by the national associations on 18 April 1909 for a bid to host the Olympics in Stockholm on the basis that suitable financial arrangements could be made.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] King Gustaf V was petitioned on 6 May 1909 following the publication of preliminary plans for the Stockholm bid that the expected cost of hosting the Games would be 415,000 kronor (£23,050 or $115,250).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Government accepted the petition on behalf of the King and supported the bid.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] On 28 May, at the meeting of the IOC in Berlin, the Swedish representatives declared that they had full financial support for hosting the next Games in Stockholm.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A deal was made with the German IOC representative on the basis that Berlin would host the 1916 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin spoke at the meeting about his concerns that Sweden should ensure that the Games take place, as he did not want a repeat of the problems with Great Britain hosting the 1908 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The news that Stockholm was to host the 1912 Olympics was received with enthusiasm by the Swedish public.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The organizing committee took de Coubertin's words to heart, and aimed to achieve an Olympic Games which removed those elements which detracted from earlier Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The committee was elected in the autumn of 1909, with Balck voted as the President of the committee, and Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf selected as Honorary President.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The committee's first meeting took place on 7 October, and on 11 October they delegated the arrangements for the individual branches of sports to the relevant governing bodies in Sweden.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were four exceptions to this, with the game shooting, modern pentathlon and mountain ascents retained by the Olympic committee, and the horse riding competitions being organized by Prince Carl, Duke of Västergötland, who was the inspector of the Swedish cavalry.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Altogether there were 187 members of these committees.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The official invitation to compete in the Games was issued on 18 November 1910 to 27 countries, either directly or through their representative on the IOC.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A further 15 countries were to have been invited, but as they had no IOC representatives, the Swedish authorities were unsure how to proceed.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Once the organizing committee for the Games received confirmation of the athletic associations in each of the 15 countries, they too were sent invitations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Some 61,800 entry forms were printed for the use of the various nations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Free transport was arranged for the invited nations' equipment, and a discount of 50 percent was arranged for competitors and delegates on the state run railway.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A daily newspaper which only covered the Olympics was arranged to be published during the Games, in both English and Swedish.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Further arrangements were made for the general arrival of visitors in order to entertain them whilst they were not at the Games; a pleasure garden was opened north of the Olympic Stadium, and a series of indoor tennis courts were converted into a restaurant.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Twelve sports venues were used in the 1912 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that more than one venue would be used for the football tournament, which has been the case ever since.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm Olympic Stadium served as one of the equestrian venues for the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Råsunda Stadium served as a venue for the 1958 FIFA World Cup and the 1995 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the initial bid document it was identified that a new stadium would be needed, initially envisaged as being located in the Östermalm Athletic Grounds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In order to save funds, it was expected that only one of the stadium's stands would be permanent, with the other three made of wood and dismantled following the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cost of that stadium was estimated at 235,000 Kronor.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Arrangements were made with the individual national committees to provide the use of Östermalm Athletic Grounds and Traneberg.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling road race was held around Mälaren, the third largest lake in Sweden.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The water events, including the swimming and the rowing, were held at Djurgårdsbrunnsviken, where a stadium was built.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Kaknäs was already used as a shooting range, but alterations were needed to accommodate shooting events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Although it was not used as the Olympic stadium as originally intended, Östermalm hosted the lawn tennis and fencing competitions after a tennis pavilion was moved there from another location.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Five other locations were considered in addition to the Östermalm Athletic Grounds to locate the Olympic Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Stockholm Olympic Stadium was built on the site of the former Stockholm Athletic Grounds in order to retain the other locations for other uses during the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] By placing it to the north of the city, the Olympic Stadium was within the immediate vicinity of other pre-existing sporting venues.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Initial funding was given to the sum of 400,000 Kr for a timber stadium but Torben Grut, the architect, also drew up alternative plans for a stone stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However it was found that the original estimate for the stone stadium would still be too expensive, and the plans were once more modified in order to simplify the design and reduce costs.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] An agreement was entered into with a contractor on 2 November 1910 that it would be transferred complete by 25 May 1912.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Games of the V Olympiad were opened on 6 July 1912.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish Royal Family left Stockholm Palace at 10:40am, and were received at the Olympic Stadium by members of the IOC.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Three thousand competing athletes had already assembled in the nearby Östermalm Athletic Grounds, and began to enter the stadium in alphabetical order by nation according to the Swedish spelling.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team entered last, but unlike the later tradition, the Greek team did not enter first.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A hymn was sung, a traditional Swedish chant was conducted and prayers were read first in Swedish and then in English.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf addressed the King on behalf of the Swedish Olympic Association.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Afterwards a trumpet fanfare was played and the Crown Prince called for cheers for the King.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The athletes in their national groups marching out of the stadium in order ended the ceremony.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish delegation at the IOC meeting in Berlin on 28 May 1909 had proposed a simple Olympic schedule containing only "pure" athletics, swimming, gymnastics and wrestling.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However other countries requested that the schedule be more comprehensive, and with that in mind they put forward a further programme at the IOC meeting in 1911 which was met with approval.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The sports which were added were the tug of war, cycling, fencing, football, horse riding, lawn tennis, rowing, shooting, skating and yacht racing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The question of adding skating to the programme was discussed once more on 7 February 1910, with the decision being made to drop it from the schedule.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was felt to be unsuitable because it was a winter sport, and it was to be part of the Nordic Games the following year.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Boxing was removed from the programme as it was unappealing to the Swedes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Art competitions were considered at a further meeting on 14 February 1910, and were subsequently added to the programme, but now art competitions are no longer regarded as official Olympic events by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] As a result, now the 1912 Summer Olympics programme considered composed of 14 sports encompassing 18 disciplines and 102 events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball, Glima (as the second Olympic demonstration of the sport after 1908 Summer Olympics) and Gotland sports were unofficial demonstration sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first year art competitions were held at the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The athletic events saw the introduction of a fully automatic timing system developed by R.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It involved attaching electromagnets to chronometers in a system which attached a control lamp to the starting gun for each race.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This resulted in the firing of the gun starting a timer which was then stopped by one of the judges at the finishing line.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The final of the men's 100 metres was expected to be a mostly American affair, and it ended up with six athletes, only one of whom was not from the United States.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It suffered from seven false starts before the athletes finally got away, with Ralph Craig winning the gold medal by 60 centimetres (24 in) in front of second place Alvah Meyer.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Donald Lippincott won bronze, 15 cm behind the second man.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Shizo Kanakuri, a Japanese marathon runner, went missing during the race.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] He lost consciousness by heatstroke and a farming family helped him to stop at a party taking place in a villa on the marathon route in order to quench his thirst, then caught a train to Stockholm and left the country the next day.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] He returned to Japan without notifying race officials.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Fifty years later, after being invited back by the Swedish authorities, he completed the race with an (unofficial) time of 54 years, 8 months, 6 days, 8 hours, 32 minutes and 20.3 seconds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Portuguese Francisco Lázaro died from heat exhaustion while running the marathon, the only athlete to die during the running of an Olympic marathon.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition to the physical toll of the event, the reported split time for the 5 km checkpoint at Stocksund (2:17:20 after a 1:48:00 start) implies an unusually slow 29:20 opening segment, followed by an unrealistically fast 10 km pace.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Martin has noted this discrepancy as a likely timing error.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] American Jim Thorpe won the pentathlon and the newly created decathlon.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Thorpe's gold medals were stripped by the International Olympic Committee in 1913, after the IOC learned that Thorpe had taken expense money for playing baseball, violating contemporary Olympic amateurism rules, before the 1912 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This moved everyone else up in the rankings.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In 1982, the IOC was convinced that the disqualification had been improper, as no protest against Thorpe's eligibility had been brought within the required 30 days, and reinstated Thorpe's medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The replicas were presented to his children in 1983, 30 years after Thorpe's death.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Finally, in 2022, the IOC posthumously declared Thorpe as the sole winner of the pentathlon and decathlon events after extensive consultations with his former competitors' families who said they had always viewed Thorpe as the winner.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic records were set in the majority of track and field events, with only the men's 200 metres, 10 km walk, standing high jump, standing broad jump, hop, step and jump, and the hurdle competitions failing to have new records set.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Tell Berna captured a gold for the 3000m and Henry S.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] "Harry" Babcock took gold for the pole vault, setting an Olympic Record at 3.95m.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Hannes Kolehmainen was the most successful in setting records at the games, with new Olympic Records set in the 5,000, 10,000 metre and cross country races.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling events at the 1912 Games were limited to a road race around Lake Mälaren, which had already been a successful route for a yearly cycling race.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Although not originally in the schedule, several countries requested that track cycling be added; however, the organizing committee stuck by their plans not to build a new track cycling stadium as the only one in Stockholm had been destroyed in order for the Olympic Stadium to be built.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Germany had specifically requested Cycle-Polo and Figure-Cycling to be added to the programme, both of which requests were turned down by the committee.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was decided to hold the road race as a time trial, and to outlaw any non-competitive cyclists acting as pacemakers.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations entered 151 athletes into the competition, which was a greater number than expected by the committee.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The largest group was from Great Britain, who had entered twelve competitors from England, another twelve from Scotland, and a further nine from Ireland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The race began on 7 July, with the athletes leaving in groups.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The first group left at 2am, with the remaining groups leaving at intervals of two minutes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The distance raced was 318 kilometres (198 mi), with South African Rudolph Lewis winning the gold medal in the individual race.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Frederick Grubb of Great Britain won the silver medal, and Carl Schutte of the United States won the bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However, the average positions of the Swedish team were better than their competitors', and so the Swedish team won the gold medal for the team competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The silver and bronze medals followed the individual victories, going to Great Britain and the United States respectively – giving Grubb and Schutte a second medal each of the same varieties.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] All of the medals in the men's competitions were split between the diving teams of the Sweden and Germany.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The men's high dive was a Swedish white out, with Swedish divers taking all three medal positions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Erik Adlerz took the gold medal, and proceeded to take the gold medal for Sweden in the 10 metre platform too.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Albert Zürner took the silver for Germany, and Gustaf Blomgren won the bronze medal for Sweden.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Another white out occurred in the 3 metre springboard with all three medals going to the German team, with Paul Günther taking gold, Hans Luber in the silver medal position and Kurt Behrens in bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A 10-metre platform event also took place for women, with Sweden taking two more medals, Greta Johansson in gold and Lisa Regnell in silver.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain's Isabelle White won the bronze medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The remaining finalists were all from Sweden.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Equestrian made its first appearance at a modern Olympics in the 1912 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Although competitions involving horse riding had been included in the programme of 1900, this was the first appearance of modern Olympic staples such as dressage, eventing and show jumping.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was expected that the competitors would be military personnel as they would have had the cavalry experience to compete.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split between the military competitions, prize riding and prize jumping.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the military competition, seven countries put forward competitors for the individual and team eventing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Each nation put forward four athletes with the exception of Denmark, which only put forward three.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Some of the countries also nominated reserves in addition to their main athletes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The total length of the course was 55 kilometres (34 mi) with the start and finish both in the grounds of the Field Riding Club.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The heat was such on the day of the event that competitors lost as much as 4.5 pounds (2.0 kg) in weight.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Swede Axel Nordlander won the individual competition, and led the Swedish eventing team to victory as well, earning himself two gold medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In second place in the individual competition was German Friedrich von Rochow, who also earned a second silver medal as the team from Germany placed second overall.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Only the bronze medals were split up between nationalities, with the American team including Guy Vernor Henry, Jr. taking the bronze for the team event, while Frenchman Jacques Cariou won the individual medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Two additional countries entered for the dressage, although only Sweden entered the maximum number of competitors.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The event resulted in Sweden taking all three medals, with the gold going to Carl Bonde, the silver to Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern and the bronze to Hans von Blixen-Finecke.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The team event saw Sweden take another gold medal, with the French team second and the German team, featuring Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia, in the bronze medal position.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The foil competition became a full Olympic event, having appeared at the 1908 Games as a demonstration sport.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Nedo Nadi and Pietro Speciale of Italy took the gold and silver medals respectively, and Richard Verderber of Austria placed third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were individual and team events in both épée and sabre.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The épée team event saw Belgium take the gold medal and Great Britain and the Netherlands in second and third place respectively.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A member of the Belgian team went on to take the individual title as well, with Paul Anspach taking the gold medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Ivan Joseph Martin Osiier of Denmark took the silver medal, and another Belgian who was not in the team event, Philippe le Hardy de Beaulieu, won the bronze medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The sabre competition was dominated by the competitors from Hungary, with their team taking the gold medal over Austria and the Netherlands.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The individual competition saw a shut out by Hungarian athletes with Jenő Fuchs winning the overall competition, Béla Békessy in second and Ervin Mészáros in third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen countries signalled their intention to enter football teams for the 1912 Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A standard cup tie system was implemented, with the final deciding the gold and silver medallists and a third/fourth position playoff deciding the bronze medal winner.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Only FIFA affiliated teams were allowed to take part, with the public draw for the tournament taking place on 18 June 1911.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The tournament itself started on 29 June.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the first round Finland defeated Italy 3–2, Austria beat Germany 5–1 and the Netherlands emerged victorious over Sweden 4–3.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The team from Great Britain, who had won the gold medal at the 1908 Summer Games, were given a bye to the second round, where they faced Hungary and won 7–0.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Finland also won their match, defeating Russia 2–1.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Denmark matched the British scoreline, winning 7–0 against Norway, and the Netherlands won against Austria 3–1.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The semi final matches pitted Great Britain against Finland, where they won 4–0, and Denmark against the Netherlands, ending in a 4–1 victory for Denmark.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Netherlands won the third/fourth place playoff by the biggest scoreline of the tournament, beating Finland 9–0.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Later on the same day the final was played in the Olympic Stadium, where Great Britain retained its gold medal against Denmark in front of 25,000 spectators.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Goals from Harold Walden, Arthur Berry and two from Gordon Hoare helped Britain to win by a margin of 4–2.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The gymnastic competition at the 1912 Games featured a single individual competition and three team events in addition to a variety of displays by the various teams.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team naturally won the Gymnastics event of the Swedish system, referred to in the programme as "Team Competition I", with fellow Scandinavian teams Denmark and Norway taking the second and third positions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition came second, with Italy taking the gold.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, one of the Italian team members, Alberto Braglia, won the individual gold for the same event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Louis Ségura of the French team won the individual silver, while another member of the Italian team, Adolfo Tunesi, won the individual bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition saw Hungary take the silver medal and the team from Great Britain in third place.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The final team competition allowed for a free choice of movements and apparatus.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was another all Scandinavian affair, with the Norwegian team emerging victorious, Finland in second and Denmark in the bronze medal position.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Modern pentathlon was competed for at the 1912 Games, marking its first appearance in the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was for these games that the five events of shooting, swimming, equestrian, fencing and cross country running were decided to make up the pentathlon.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was spread out across five days from 7 through to 12 July, ending with the cross country race.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Only men participated in the event, although a woman named Helen Preece was briefly enrolled to compete until the organizing committee ultimately denied her entry.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] For the shooting element, each competitor was allowed to bring their own pistol.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The shooting part of the competition was won by Gösta Åsbrink, with Georg de Laval and Gösta Lilliehöök in second and third place respectively, all three representing Sweden.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The swimming event was three lengths, each of 100 metres (330 ft), with the athletes split into eight heats and times going forward to calculate positions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Ralph Clilverd of Great Britain won this event, with Edmond Bernhardt of Austria in second and de Laval in third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The fencing competition saw each competitor face off against each other.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Several opponents were noted for their particular skill in the event with Åke Grönhagen of Sweden coming first with 24 wins, Jean de Mas Latrie of France second with 23, Sidney Stranne of Sweden in third with 21 and Patton of the United States close behind with 20.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen of the competitors cleared the equestrian course without any penalties, with Grönhagen winning the event, Bror Mannström of Sweden in second and de Laval third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cross country run was over 4,000 metres and started in the Olympic Stadium itself.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The event was run as a time trial with competitors leaving one minute apart.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] As this was the final event, the winning competitors were announced after the race, with Lilliehöök winning the gold medal, Åsbrink taking silver and de Laval, bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The highest placed non-Swedish competitor was Patton, who finished fifth.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The rowing events at the 1912 Olympics did not prove popular with the public.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was put down to the "fatigue" of the public due to the volume of sporting events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The eight competition was split into heats, with two teams in each heat.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The two British crews were lucky not to be drawn against each other, with the team from Leander Club facing New College, Oxford in the final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Leander won by a length with a time of 6:15.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The coxed four followed a similar format to the eights, with the German team from Ludwigshafener Ruderverein defeating Britain's Thames Rowing Club in the final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition for the coxed four, inriggers was much smaller, with only four nations competing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Danish team defeated Sweden in the final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The single sculls heats proved controversial with the first round race between Mart Kuusik and Alfred Heinrich being re-run after a protest by Heinrich.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Cecil McVilly was disqualified in the first round after colliding with the boat of Martin Stahnke.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Wally Kinnear of Great Britain defeated Polydore Veirman of Belgium in the final, with Kinnear winning the matchup easily.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The yachts for the sailing competition assembled at Nynäshamn on 19 July, along with the other vessels that were to take part in an Olympic regatta.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The racing itself started the following day with the 12 metre class.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were only three nations and yachts competing in this event, the hosts Sweden, as well as Norway and Finland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Norway won the gold medal, Sweden the silver and Finland came in last place, winning bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 10 metre class had the same number of countries entering it, although this time Sweden entered two yachts and Russia competed instead of Norway.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish yacht *Kitty* was the winning vessel, with the Finnish boat in second and the Russians coming third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A slightly improved field was featured in the 8 metre class, with four countries entering two yachts each.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The medals were awarded to exactly the same nations as the 12 metre class, another all Scandinavian affair.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 6 metre class saw the most diverse field of any of the sailing events at the 1912 Olympics: six countries entered a total of nine yachts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] France and Denmark competed in their only sailing event, along with Sweden, sending two yachts each.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Those three nations were the successful in the event, with the French yacht *Mac Miche* taking the gold, the Danish *Nurdug II* taking silver and the Swedish *Kerstin* placing third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were eighteen shooting events at the 1912 Olympics, of which eight were team events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split predominantly into three sections: military rifle shooting, shooting with miniature rifles, pistols and revolvers, and clay bird and running deer shooting.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish and American competitors were the most successful at the competition, with seven gold medals each, although Sweden won a total of seventeen medals while the United States team won fourteen.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] 64-year-old Oscar Swahn, part of the Swedish single shot running deer team, is still the oldest gold medal winner in Olympic history.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In swimming, Hawaiian Duke Kahanamoku won the 100 metre freestyle for the United States, who also saw Harry Hebner win gold in the 100 metre backstroke.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Canadian team also took two gold medals, both by George Hodgson in the 400 and 1,500 metre events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The German swimming team won all three medals in the 200 metre breaststroke, with the gold going to Walter Bathe, who won a further gold in the 400 metre breaststroke.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Australasian team was victorious in the men's relay, with the United States finishing in the silver medal position and Great Britain placing third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Games saw the implementation of swimming events for women, with the 100 metre freestyle and 400 metre team relay taking place.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Fanny Durack won the individual contest, breaking the world record for the distance in the fourth heat.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Her fellow Australian Mina Wylie won the silver medal, and Jennie Fletcher of Great Britain came third to take the bronze medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The British team had further success in the women's relay, winning the team relay with the German team in second place and the Austrian team in third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Because only four countries entered the relay there were no heats; only a final was held.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The United States did not field a women's team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic Records were set in all swimming events at the 1912 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Tennis on covered courts was agreed initially for the 1912 Games, with competitions run for gentlemen's singles and doubles, ladies' singles, and mixed doubles.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoor tournament was confirmed once the Östermalm Athletic Grounds were completed in late 1911, with the plans modified to have both indoor and outdoor tournaments.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Six countries sent players for the covered court competitions, with representatives from Sweden, Great Britain, Denmark, France, Australasia, and Bohemia appearing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Included in this lineup was Australasia's only competitor, Anthony Wilding from New Zealand, who was also the reigning Wimbledon gentlemen's champion.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The indoor knockout competition started on 5 May, and continued as expected until the semi-final round where Wilding was beaten by Britain's Charles P.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The British player met Frenchman André Gobert in the final, but Gobert was victorious over the Englishman in straight sets.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Wilding took the bronze medal in a playoff against another British player, Arthur Lowe.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoors tennis competition saw 70 players enter from 12 nations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However, Great Britain did not enter any competitors as the dates of the outdoor competition clashed with the 1912 Wimbledon Championships, despite attempts by the British authorities to convince the Olympic organizing committee to change the dates.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Other noted tennis players refused to compete at the Olympics and instead attended Wimbledon.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals in the gentlemen's singles ended up being decided between two South Africans, with Charles Winslow and Harold Kitson playing each other.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The duo also competed as a pair in the gentlemen's doubles and took the gold medal, beating the Austrians Felix Pipes and Arthur Zborzil.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Marguerite Broquedis of France defeated Dorothea Koring of Germany in the ladies' singles for the gold medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the mixed doubles Koring teamed up with Heinrich Schomburgk to win the gold, the duo defeating Sigrid Fick and Gunnar Setterwall of Sweden in the final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The tug of war competition was scheduled to take place between 7 and 12 July, with two matches taking place each day.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However, out of the five countries which elected to enter the competition, only two actually appeared.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain arrived for its match against Bohemia, but the opposition team was nowhere to be found.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The same thing happened once more for the second match, with the Swedish team, made up of policemen from Stockholm, arriving to find that the Austrian team had not arrived.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was announced as the winners of the match in the Austrians' absence.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] On the second day of the competition, Great Britain took on Sweden, the only occasion where both teams actually turned up for the bout.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The British team were made up of the winners of the gold medal in the same event at the 1908 Games, with the exception of John Sewell and Mathias Hynes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] As the British team also consisted of policemen, the bout ended up effectively being between the City of London Police and the Stockholm Police, with the Swedish team winning 2–0.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Due to the non-appearance of the team from Luxembourg, that one match ended up being the entire tug of war event at the 1912 Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was awarded the gold medal and Great Britain the silver.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The water polo tournament was set up on a modified elimination system as there were six teams entered.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The first round saw the British team defeating the Belgian team, Sweden defeating the French team and Austria defeating Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Lots were drawn to determine which match would take place in the second round as there were three teams left in the competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain were drawn to face Sweden, who they defeated.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Austria automatically qualified for the final against the winner of the Britain-Sweden matchup.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain won the gold medal in the event, defeating Austria 8–0.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Playoff matches were then played between each pair of defeated teams in order to decide the second and third places.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden and Belgium played off after a further three matches to decide the silver and bronze medal positions, with Sweden emerging victorious 4–2.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The nations at the 1912 Games entered a total of 267 wrestlers, although the actual competitors who appeared in Sweden were fewer, with 171 actually turning up to compete.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Greco-Roman wrestling was the only style of wrestling competed for at the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The bouts took place in the open air in an area of the Olympic stadium, with the wrestlers split according to weight into five divisions: featherweight, lightweight, middleweight A (later referred to as middleweight), middleweight B (later referred to as light heavyweight) and heavyweight.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The skills of the competitors from Finland were noted in the featherweight competition, with Kaarlo Koskelo taking the gold medal, while German Georg Gerstäcker took silver and a further medal went to Finland with Otto Lasanen taking bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The lightweight class drew the most attention from the public, with Emil Väre winning gold after beating all of his opponents by pin rather than by points.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Swedish wrestlers Gustaf Malmström and Edvin Mattiasson took the silver and bronze medals respectively.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Claes Johanson won Sweden's only gold medal in the middleweight competition, with his fellow finalist from Russia, Martin Klein, retiring before fighting Johanson in the final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was due to the semi-final match between Klein and Alfred Asikainen of Finland lasting 11 hours and forty minutes, although they took breaks for refreshments every half-hour.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Klein was awarded the silver medal and Asikainen the bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The light heavyweight competition saw another marathon length match, with the bout between Anders Ahlgren of Sweden and Ivar Böhling of Finland for the gold medal lasting more than nine hours.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The match was then declared a draw with both athletes being awarded the silver medal as neither won the match.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The bronze medal went to Hungary's Béla Varga, who was defeated by Ahlgren in the semi-final match.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Yrjö Saarela of Finland was victorious in the heavyweight competition after having placed second in the light heavyweight event at the 1908 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Johan Olin took another medal for Finland with the silver and Søren Marinus Jensen repeated his bronze medal at the 1908 Olympics with another for Denmark.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Summer Olympics saw the introduction of art competitions at the Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Events were implemented for literature, sculpture, painting, architecture and music.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Walter Winans won the gold medal for his sculpture, *An American Trotter*, which added to his previous gold medal for the running deer (double shot) competition at the 1908 Olympics and the silver medal in the running deer competition in 1912.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Baron Pierre de Coubertin, President of the IOC and founder of the modern Olympic movement, won the gold medal for literature.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] He actually entered the competition under the pseudonyms of Georges Hohrod and Martin Eschbach from Germany.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of the sculpture competition, only gold medals were issued.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Italian Riccardo Barthelemy won the medal for music with his *Olympic Triumphal March*, and fellow countryman Giovanni Pellegrini won the gold for painting.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swiss architects Eugène-Edouard Monod and Alphonse Laverrière shared the gold for their stadium design.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The sole silver medal, for sculpture, went to Frenchman Georges Dubois for his *Model of the entrance to a modern stadium*.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the evening of 7 July, demonstrations took place in the Olympic Stadium of sports from the Swedish island of Gotland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] These began at 7:30pm with a demonstration of Pärk, a type of tennis with seven players a side.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] At the same time, at the other end of the stadium, a type of Icelandic wrestling called Glima was demonstrated.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Once those displays had concluded, further demonstrations were made of the Swedish sport varpa, similar to quoits, and stångstörtning, a version of the caber toss.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The three disciplines showcased were pärk, varpa and stångstörtning.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball was also demonstrated at the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A game was played between the United States, the nation where the game was developed, and Sweden, the host nation.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The game was held on Monday, 15 July 1912 and started at 10 a.m. on the Ostermalm Athletic Grounds in Stockholm.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Americans were represented by various members of the American Olympic track and field athletics delegation, while the Swedish team was the Vesterås Baseball Club, which had been formed in 1910 as the first baseball club in Sweden.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Four of the Americans played for Sweden, as the Swedish pitchers and catchers were inexperienced.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] One Swede eventually relieved Adams and Nelson, the American pitchers.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Six innings were played, with the Americans not batting in the sixth and allowing the Swedes to have six outs in their half of the inning.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The game was umpired by George Wright, a retired American National League baseball player.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations competed at the 1912 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt participated for the first time, as did Luxembourg, Iceland, Portugal, and Serbia.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Japan also made their Olympic debut, marking the first appearance of an Asian country at an Olympic Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Chile made its first appearance as a national team, with fourteen athletes attending the Games, although it had previously entered one individual at the 1896 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first time that athletes from Armenia had competed in the Olympics, as part of the team from Turkey (the officially recognised name for the Ottoman Empire).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Serbia's appearance was the only time it attended an Olympic Games as an independent nation until the 2008 Summer Olympics, almost one hundred years later.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The only nation that participated in the previous games in London 1908 but was absent in Stockholm 1912 was Argentina.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality they were two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] At the time, Australasia (Australia and New Zealand), Canada and South Africa were all part of the British Empire.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt was de jure under the control of Turkey, but had been de facto run by the British since 1882.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was the last Olympics that allowed "private entries", i.e. individual athletes that were not part of a country's officially selected team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Arnold Jackson was one such private entry; he won the 1500 metres by 0.1 seconds, ahead of an American trio, in what was acclaimed at the time to be "the greatest race ever run".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] His medal is still credited to the United Kingdom, however.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] These are the top 10 nations that won medals at the 1912 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The medals themselves included solid gold medals, the last time these were given out.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The **1924 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1924*), officially the **Games of the VIII Olympiad** (French: *Jeux de la VIIIe olympiade*) and officially branded as **Paris 1924**, were an international multi-sport event held in Paris, France.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 5 July, but some competitions had already started on 4 May.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The Games were the second to be hosted by Paris (after 1900), making it the first city to host the Olympics twice.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The selection process for the 1924 Summer Olympics consisted of six bids, and Paris was selected ahead of Amsterdam, Barcelona, Los Angeles, Prague, and Rome.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 20th IOC Session in Lausanne in 1921.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The cost of these Games was estimated to be 10,000,000 F (equivalent to €10.9 million in 2025).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] With total receipts at 5,496,610 F (equivalent to €5.97 million in 2025), the Olympics resulted in a hefty loss despite daily crowds of up to 60,000.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and overall medals, having 229 athletes competing compared to France's 401.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] This would be the last Summer Games hosted by France until 2024.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] 126 events in 23 disciplines, comprising 17 sports, were part of the Olympic program in 1924.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The Jeux de L’Enfance, a program of youth sports competitions and activities, were held by Olympic organizers alongside the Games in cooperation with the YMCA.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Seventeen sports venues were used in the 1924 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Stade de Colombes served as the final venue for the 1938 FIFA World Cup between Italy and Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] A total of 44 nations were represented at the 1924 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Germany was still absent, having not been invited by the Organizing Committee.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] China (although it did not compete), Ecuador, Ireland, Lithuania, and Uruguay attended the Olympic Games for the first time, while the Philippines competed for first time in an Olympic Games as a nation (though it first participated in the 1900 Summer Olympic Games).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Latvia and Poland also attended the Summer Olympic Games for the first time (having both appeared earlier at the 1924 Winter Olympics in Chamonix).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The 1924 Olympics saw a return of the following nations: Austria, Bulgaria, Cuba, Haiti, Hungary, Mexico, Romania and Turkey.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] At the time, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, South Africa and Ireland were all dominions of the British Empire.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] India was also part of British Empire, but was not a dominion.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] United States, France, Brazil, Japan, etc) and the international community as a whole (i.e League of Nations) the term dominion, used internally in the British Empire, was very ambiguous, meaning "something between a colony and state".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] It was only years later with the Statute of Westminster 1931 that this ambiguity would be dispelled.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] And Philippines was an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals the 1924 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The 1924 Summer Olympics also included art competitions across five disciplines: architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture, for works inspired by sport-related themes, were medal-eligible events at the time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Art competitions were held from the 1912 Summer Olympics until the 1948 Summer Olympics, but were discontinued over the amateurism controversy.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Medals in art competitions are no longer recognized by the IOC as part of the total medal count.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] In architecture, no gold medal was awarded while the silver was awarded to the pair of Alfréd Hajós and Dezső Lauber of Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Hajós became one of only two Olympians ever to have won medals in both sport (two golds in swimming at the 1896 Summer Olympics) and art Olympic competitions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The bronze was awarded to Julien Médecin of Monaco, who became the first Monégasque competitor to win an Olympic medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] In literature, one gold, which was awarded to Géo-Charles of France, two silvers to Josef Petersen of Denmark and Margaret Stuart of Great Britain, and two bronzes to Charles Gonnet of France and Oliver Gogarty of Ireland, were awarded.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Two compositions, entitled "The Land Where the Rose is Grown" and "O Vigila (now let the games begin)", that were part of the literature competition, were also part of the music competitions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The compositions were made by George Bamber of Great Britain, though no medals were awarded in the music competition as the jury could not reach a consensus to award medals for any of the competitors.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] In painting, Jean Jacoby of Luxembourg won the gold medal, becoming the first Luxembourgish competitor to win an Olympic gold medal, Jack Butler Yeats of Ireland won the silver, becoming the first Irish competitor to win an Olympic medal, and Johan van Hell of the Netherlands won the bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] In sculpture, Konstantinos Dimitriadis of Greece won the gold medal, Frantz Heldenstein of Luxembourg won the silver, and two bronze medals were awarded, one to Jean René Gauguin of Denmark and the other to Claude-Léon Mascaux of France.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The 1924 Summer Olympics was the second edition of the Summer Olympics to be held in Paris.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] 100 years later, the city has hosted the games once again with the 2024 Summer Olympics, marking its third time, becoming the second city ever to host the Summer Olympics three times (after London, which hosted the 1908, 1948, and 2012 Games).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Paris 2024 also marks the centenary of Chamonix 1924, which in turn marks the centenary of the Winter Olympics; making Paris 2024 the sixth Olympic Games hosted by France (three Summer Olympics and three Winter Olympics), and the first French Olympics since the 1992 Winter Games in Albertville.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Notable debuts of participating countries for the Paris 1924 Olympics include Ireland, Latvia, Lithuania, Philippines, Poland, Romania, and Uruguay; all of which celebrated their centenary participation at the 2024 Summer Olympics back in Paris.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] One venue from the 1924 Games was used in the 2024 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The extensively renovated and downsized main stadium, known since 1928 as Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir, hosted field hockey.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] The last surviving competitor of the 1924 Summer Olympics was Croatian swimmer Ivo Pavelić, who died on 22 February 2011 at the age of 103; he competed for Yugoslavia, which Croatia was part of at the time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1924-summer-olympics] Continuation of Jeux de L’Enfance, games for youth sports and competition, from the Paris 1924 was embodied through the creation of Youth Olympics Games inaugurating in Singapore with the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics with 3,600 athletes aged 14–18 from 204 nations competing in 201 events in 26 sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The **1936 Summer Olympics** (German: *Olympische Sommerspiele 1936*), officially the **Games of the XI Olympiad** (German: *Spiele der XI.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Olympiade*) and branded as **Berlin 1936**, were an international multi-sport event held from 1 to 16 August 1936 in Berlin, Germany.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Berlin won the right to host the Games over Barcelona at the 29th IOC Session in 1931.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the second and last occasion on which the International Olympic Committee (IOC) chose a host by a ballot in which the bidding cities themselves could vote; later rules barred cities that hosted the vote from being selected.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Games had been awarded to Germany during the Weimar Republic, but by 1936 the country was governed by the Nazi regime, and Adolf Hitler's government treated the Olympics as an opportunity for propaganda.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] To project an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, the authorities temporarily removed antisemitic signage and softened the most visible forms of persecution for the duration of the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] At the same time, the German Olympic authorities barred nearly all Jewish and Romani athletes from the national team; the fencer Helene Mayer, who had one Jewish parent, was the only such athlete to represent Germany.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] A movement to boycott or relocate the Games developed in several countries—Czechoslovakia, France, the Netherlands, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United States—but it ultimately failed.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, the largest number at any Olympics to that point.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] These were the first Games to be televised and the first to feature a torch relay carrying the Olympic flame from Olympia to the host city—a ceremony devised for Berlin that became a permanent Olympic tradition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part film *Olympia*, which pioneered techniques still used in sports cinematography.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Jesse Owens of the United States won four gold medals in the sprint and long jump events, and became the most successful athlete to compete in Berlin, while Germany was the most successful country overall with 101 medals (38 of them gold); the United States placed a distant second with 57 medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Henri de Baillet-Latour.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] For the next 12 years, no Olympic Games were held due to the immense world disruption caused by the Second World War.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1948 (the Winter Games in St.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Moritz, Switzerland, and then the Summer Games in London, England).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] At the 28th IOC Session in Berlin in May 1930, fourteen cities indicated an intention to bid for the 1936 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] By the 29th Session, held in Barcelona in April 1931, only Barcelona and Berlin remained in contention; the other cities—Alexandria, Budapest, Buenos Aires, Cologne, Dublin, Frankfurt, Helsinki, Lausanne, Montevideo, Nuremberg, Rio de Janeiro, and Rome—had withdrawn.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Several of these cities later hosted the Games: Helsinki in 1952, Rome in 1960, Barcelona in 1992 and Rio de Janeiro in 2016.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 Games were the first for which the host was decided by a vote of each individual IOC member rather than by the assembled Session alone.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The deadline for ballots was 13 May 1931, two weeks after the Barcelona Session.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Of 67 voting members, 19 cast ballots during the Session and 40 by post to the IOC headquarters in Lausanne; eight abstained.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The result was 43 votes for Berlin and 16 for Barcelona.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Barcelona's prospects were probably weakened by the political uncertainty that followed the proclamation of the Second Spanish Republic days before the Session.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] After the Nazi seizure of power in 1933 and the regime's early antisemitic measures, some IOC members privately discussed moving the Games, and the US Olympic Association briefly suggested transferring them to Rome.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler's government gave assurances that Jewish athletes would not be excluded from the German team, and the proposal was not seriously pursued.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Awarded to Berlin in 1931 under the Weimar Republic, the Games took on a new character after the Nazi takeover of January 1933, as the regime grasped their value as international propaganda.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler regarded the Games as a chance to promote his government and its ideology of Aryan supremacy.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The official Nazi paper, the *Völkischer Beobachter*, had argued in the strongest terms that Jewish and black athletes should be barred from the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] As the Games approached, however, the regime worked to soften Germany's international image: signs reading "Jews not welcome" (German: *Juden unerwünscht*) were taken down from public places for the duration, and overt antisemitic agitation was muted.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The effort extended to the removal of people the regime considered undesirable.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In July 1936 the Ministry of the Interior authorised Berlin's police to detain the city's Romani and confine them in a special camp at Marzahn, on the city's outskirts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Five months before the opening ceremony, in March 1936, Germany had remilitarised the Rhineland in breach of the Treaty of Versailles, heightening international tension in the months before the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In line with Nazi directives, the German Olympic Committee effectively barred German athletes who were Jewish or Roma, or of such ancestry, from competing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The most prominent excluded athlete was the high jumper Gretel Bergmann, who was dropped from the team shortly after equalling the German record of 1.60 m in June 1936.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Others kept off the team included the record-holding track-and-field athlete Lilli Henoch, the tennis player Daniel Prenn, the boxer Erich Seelig and the Sinti boxer Johann Trollmann.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Helene Mayer—already an Olympic champion who had emigrated to the United States—returned to fence for Germany and won a silver medal, the only athlete of Jewish descent on the German team, a token inclusion intended to deflect foreign criticism.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The exclusions also reached the organisers.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Although the Olympic flame had been reintroduced at the 1928 Summer Olympics, Berlin staged the first torch relay, carrying a flame kindled at Olympia in Greece to the host city through seven countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The concept, organised by Diem, established the modern convention later used at every Games, and Riefenstahl incorporated the relay into *Olympia*.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Olympic Village lay at Elstal in Wustermark, about 30 km west of central Berlin, and comprised low dormitories, a large "Dining Hall of the Nations", training facilities and a swimming hall.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] After the Games the site was absorbed by the Wehrmacht and later used by Soviet forces as a military camp; parts of it, including the dormitory used by Jesse Owens, have been restored more recently.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Twenty-two venues were used, most of them in the purpose-built Reichssportfeld complex, which had been planned for the cancelled 1916 Summer Olympics and was completed in 1934–36.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The centrepiece Olympic Stadium seated about 100,000; sailing was held in the Bay of Kiel, later reused for the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were the first to be carried on live television.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Using Telefunken equipment, the German Post Office transmitted more than 70 hours of black-and-white coverage to public viewing rooms in Berlin and Potsdam, where more than 162,000 people in all followed the competitions on screens outside the stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Radio carried the Games more widely still, in 28 languages across some 2,500 broadcasts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were also an early showcase for colour photography, using Germany's newly developed Agfacolor film.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The filmmaker Leni Riefenstahl recorded the Games for her two-part documentary *Olympia*, released in 1938.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Games were among the most lavish staged to that point, and most of the spending lay well outside the organising committee's own accounts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] From 1933 the Reich Ministry of the Interior directed a vast building programme that the regime folded into its public-works and job-creation schemes, and historians have treated this state investment—rather than ticket income—as the truer measure of what the Games cost.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Its centrepiece, the new Olympic Stadium, was built in barely two years at a cost of around 42 million Reichsmark; with the wider Reichssportfeld, the Olympic Village and new transport links, the state's outlay dwarfed the committee's budget.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler also prized the Games as a way to earn scarce foreign currency at a time of dwindling German reserves, later claiming they had brought in large sums.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The committee's own books were comparatively modest: ticket sales brought in about 7.5 million RM and an operating profit of over one million RM.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The city of Berlin reported costs of about 16.5 million RM, while the national government's total spending was never published in full and has been estimated at around US$30 million.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The sporting programme ran from 1 to 16 August 1936 and was framed by elaborate opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony took place at the Olympic Stadium on 1 August 1936.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The airship *Hindenburg* flew over the stadium trailing the Olympic flag.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] After Hitler's arrival the parade of nations proceeded, with Greece first and the host nation last; some teams gave the Nazi salute or the similar Olympic salute as they passed Hitler's box, with French Olympians giving a Roman salute, while the United States and a few others did not.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Greek team that led the parade was headed by Spyridon Louis, winner of the marathon at the first modern Olympics in 1896, who presented Hitler with an olive branch from Olympia.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Hitler then declared the Games open; in keeping with Olympic protocol his part was confined to the set formula—"I proclaim the Games of Berlin, celebrating the eleventh Olympiad of the modern era, to be open"—his only public statement during the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] A torch-bearer then ran into the arena to light the cauldron, and thousands of pigeons were released.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] During the ceremony the Olympic Hymn—specially composed by Richard Strauss, who conducted it himself—received its première; Strauss had taken the commission only after the writer Gerhart Hauptmann failed to supply a text, and he privately dismissed the piece even as he led it.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The programme comprised 129 events in 25 disciplines across 19 sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Basketball, canoeing and handball made their Olympic debuts; handball would not return until the 1972 Summer Olympics, while polo made its fifth and final Olympic appearance.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Baseball and gliding were held as demonstration sports, and art competitions awarded medals, as did feats of alpinism and aeronautics recognised at the closing ceremony.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] National strengths were pronounced across the individual sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The host nation owed its place atop the medal table chiefly to gymnastics, rowing and the equestrian events, in which German riders won all six golds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Athletics, the largest sport, was dominated by the United States, whose men won twelve track-and-field golds; Helen Stephens took two of the six women's events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In the pool the men's programme became a duel between the US and Japan, while Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands, the outstanding swimmer of the Games, led Dutch dominance of the women's events; US women instead won both diving titles.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] France's Robert Charpentier won three cycling golds, and the fencing titles fell mainly to Italy and Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The team events produced their own milestones.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The United States won the first Olympic basketball tournament, beating Canada 19–8 in a final played outdoors on a rain-soaked clay court, with the game's inventor James Naismith on hand to present the medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Germany won the inaugural field handball competition, an eleven-a-side outdoor game, and Hungary took the water polo, a sport it would go on to dominate.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Italy won the football and India a third successive hockey gold, while polo, won by Argentina, was contested for the last time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The outstanding individual performer was Jesse Owens of the United States, who won gold in the 100 m, 200 m, long jump, and 4×100 m relay.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In the long jump his German rival Luz Long offered him advice after he nearly failed to qualify, and the two were publicly cordial.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Mack Robinson, brother of Jackie Robinson, took 200 m silver behind Owens.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In the 800 m, John Woodruff won gold after deliberately slowing to free himself when boxed in.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Jack Lovelock of New Zealand won the 1500 m in a world-record 3:47.8.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Glenn Morris of the United States set a world record of 7,900 points to lead an American medal sweep, and Ondina Valla took the 80 m hurdles to become the first Italian woman to win an Olympic title, in a final so close that the first four finishers were given the same time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] German athletes were strong in several sports, sweeping all six equestrian golds and, in the gymnasts Konrad Frey and Alfred Schwarzmann, producing two triple gold medallists.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The equestrian team eventing title owed much to Konrad von Wangenheim, who finished the cross-country phase despite breaking his collarbone in a fall and returned the next day—his arm in a sling—to complete the jumping after he and his horse fell again.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Rie Mastenbroek of the Netherlands won three swimming golds and a silver, and the Estonian Kristjan Palusalu became the only wrestler to win both the freestyle and Greco-Roman heavyweight titles at a single Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Egyptian weightlifter Khadr El Touni won the middleweight gold with a world-record total, beating the German silver medallist by a wide margin.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In the football tournament, Italy—coached by Vittorio Pozzo between their two FIFA World Cup wins—took gold; the result was claimed by supporters of Benito Mussolini as a vindication of fascism.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Peru had beaten Austria 4–2 after extra time amid a disputed pitch invasion, but the IOC ordered a replay behind closed doors; Peru refused and withdrew from the Games, as did Colombia in sympathy.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] On its Olympic football debut, Japan came from two goals down to beat the favoured Swedes 3–2 before being eliminated by Italy in the next round.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] India won its third consecutive hockey gold, defeating Germany 8–1 in the final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In the marathon, the Korean runners Sohn Kee-chung and Nam Sung-yong won gold and bronze while competing for Japan, which then ruled Korea.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] More than half a century later, Sohn carried the Olympic flame into the stadium at the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The United States eight, from the University of Washington, won the rowing title with a come-from-behind final, later recounted in *The Boys in the Boat*.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The 13-year-old US Marjorie Gestring won the 3 m springboard, and Betty Robinson, the 1928 100 m champion who had nearly died in a 1931 plane crash, returned to win gold in the 4×100 m relay.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The American Jewish sprinters Marty Glickman and Sam Stoller were dropped from the 4×100 m relay on the morning of the race in favour of Owens and Ralph Metcalfe; the decision has been widely attributed to a wish not to embarrass the German hosts, though the reasons remain disputed.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Games closed on the evening of 16 August 1936 before a crowd of more than 100,000 in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Historians have described the closing as more sombre and militaristic than the opening, marked by columns of soldiers and fireworks.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] As the ceremony reached its climax, searchlights ringed the arena to form a "dome of light" overhead, the five-ringed Olympic flag was slowly lowered, and the flame that had burned since 1 August was extinguished as the spectators joined in a closing choral hymn.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] IOC president Henri de Baillet-Latour formally declared the Games closed.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] These were the last Olympics of his presidency and, as it proved, the last for twelve years; the 1940 Games had already been awarded to Tokyo at the IOC session held in Berlin on 31 July 1936, before the Olympics even opened.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Two unusual special awards were also recognised in connection with the closing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] An Olympic gold for alpinism went to the mountaineers Günter and Hettie Dyhrenfurth for their Himalayan expeditions, and the only Olympic gold ever awarded for aeronautics went to the Swiss pilot Hermann Schreiber for the first glider flight across the Alps; neither prize was contested again.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Forty-nine nations competed, up from 37 in 1932.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Five made their first Olympic appearance: Afghanistan, Bermuda, Bolivia, Costa Rica and Liechtenstein.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Several nations returned after missing 1932, while Ireland and Spain competed in 1932 but were absent from Berlin.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Sources give the number of participants differently, largely because of how the art competitions are counted.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives the figure of 3,963 athletes—3,632 men and 331 women—in the sporting events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The twelve nations that won the most medals at the 1936 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] As at every Games from 1912 to 1948, medals were also awarded in art competitions for works inspired by sport.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The 1936 edition was the largest the Olympics ever staged, with fifteen events across five categories—architecture, literature, music, painting and sculpture—and the entries were shown in an exhibition on the Kaiserdamm that drew some 70,000 visitors.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] A novelty that year was that the prize-winning musical works were performed: the German composer Werner Egk took the orchestral gold for his *Olympic Festive Music*.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] With many French and British artists staying away, German entrants dominated, winning twelve of the thirty-two medals and five of the nine golds; the judges withheld medals entirely in three events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The art competitions were dropped after 1948; the IOC's currently recognizes them as official and its database give Germany a combined total of 101 medals for the 1936 Games, which includes 12 medals won in art competitions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Prior to and during the Games, there was considerable debate outside Germany over whether the competition should be allowed or discontinued.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] A number of campaigns to boycott or relocate the Games emerged in the United Kingdom, France, Sweden, Czechoslovakia, the Netherlands, and the United States.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The most consequential debate took place in the United States.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The protests were ultimately unsuccessful; forty-nine teams from around the world participated in the 1936 Games, the largest number of participating nations of any Olympics to that point.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Traditionally, the US sent one of the largest teams to the Olympics, and there was a considerable debate over whether the nation should participate in the 1936 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Americans Milton Green and Norman Cahners refused to attend, and American Jewish organizations, such as the American Jewish Congress and the Jewish Labor Committee, supported a boycott.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Mahoney, president of the Amateur Athletic Union (AAU), contested that racial discrimination was a violation of Olympic rules and that participation in the Games was amount to an indirect endorsement of the Third Reich.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Avery Brundage, then of the American Olympic Committee, opposed the boycott, maintaining that politics had no place in sport and that the Olympic movement would be undermined if nations restricted participation by race or creed.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Brundage would be later accused of being a Soviet sympathizer for his controversial stance on the Soviet sports system that allowed them to circumvent the amateur rules.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Most African-American newspapers supported participation in the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Philadelphia *Tribune* and the *Chicago Defender* both agreed that black victories would undermine Nazi views of Aryan supremacy and spark renewed African-American pride.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Eventually, Brundage won the debate, convincing the Amateur Athletic Union to close a vote in favor of sending an American team to the Berlin Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Mahoney's efforts to incite a boycott of the Olympic games in the United States failed, although some athletes like Harvard University track star Milton Green chose to sit at home.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] US President Franklin Roosevelt and his administration did not become involved in the debate, due to a tradition of allowing the Olympic Committee to operate independently of government influence.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Several American diplomats including William E.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Dodd, the American ambassador to Berlin, and George Messersmith, head of the US legation in Vienna, opposed the decision to participate in the games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Jewish Labour Committee staged a "World Labour Athletic Carnival" in New York during as an alternative sporting event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Spanish government led by the newly elected left-wing Popular Front boycotted the Games and the Government of Catalonia organized the People's Olympiad as a parallel event in Barcelona.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Some 6,000 athletes from 49 countries registered.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] However, the People's Olympiad was aborted because of the outbreak of the Spanish Civil War just one day before the event was due to start.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had not participated in international sporting events since the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet government was not invited to the 1920 Games, with the Russian Civil War still raging, and they did not participate in the 1924 Summer Olympics and forward on ideological grounds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Instead, through the auspices of the Red Sport International, it had participated in a left-wing workers' alternative, the Spartakiad, since 1928.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The USSR had intended to attend the People's Olympiad in Barcelona until it was cancelled; the Soviets did attend the Spartakiad-sponsored 1937 Workers' Summer Olympiad in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union started competing in the Olympics in 1952, when Joseph Stalin realized that they could use the event to fulfil their political and ideological agenda.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] In France, the Jewish fencer Albert Wolff qualified for the national team but withdrew on principle.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Maccabi World Union declined an invitation on behalf of Mandatory Palestine, and two Turkish fencers, Halet Çambel and Suat Fetgeri Aşani—among the first Muslim women to compete at the Olympics—reportedly refused an introduction to Hitler.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Historians widely regard the Berlin Games as a major propaganda success for the Nazi regime, though they differ over how far that success reached.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The US Holocaust Memorial Museum describes them as "a resounding propaganda success" that projected an image of a peaceful, tolerant Germany, and notes that the forty-nine nations who took part lent the regime legitimacy in the eyes of both foreign and domestic audiences.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Most contemporary press coverage was favourable; US newspapers echoed a *New York Times* report that the Games had put Germany "back in the fold of nations".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Astute diplomats and correspondents stationed in Germany were less easily fooled, but many ordinary visitors and much of the foreign media came away impressed.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Mandell, in the first major English-language study, *The Nazi Olympics* (1971), argued that the regime's unprecedented mass pageantry overwhelmed the critical judgement of visiting journalists, businessmen and diplomats.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Other historians stress that the result turned on the failure of the boycott movement and on the willingness of officials to accept the regime's assurances, rather than on propaganda alone.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's four gold medals became the most enduring popular memory of the Games and were widely seen as a rebuke to Nazi racial theory, though Germany still finished well clear at the top of the medal table.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Owens said he had been treated cordially in Germany and reserved his bitterness for the segregation he faced on returning home, noting that President Franklin D.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Roosevelt neither received nor congratulated him.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The image of a tolerant Germany did not outlast the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Once the foreign visitors had left, anti-Jewish measures resumed and persecution intensified, leading to the Kristallnacht pogrom of November 1938 and, in September 1939, the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Several 1936 Olympians were later murdered in the Holocaust, among them the Polish competitors Roman Kantor and Ilia Szrajbman, both killed at Majdanek.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The war forced the cancellation of the 1940 and 1944 Games, and the Olympics did not resume until London 1948.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Games left a lasting cultural and sporting imprint.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Leni Riefenstahl's film *Olympia* (1938) is regarded both as a landmark in cinema—for innovations such as underwater and slow-motion photography that influenced later sports filmmaking—and as a work of state propaganda.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The torch relay and the live television coverage introduced in Berlin became permanent features of the modern Games, and the Olympic Stadium survived the war to be renovated for the 2006 FIFA World Cup final.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] Owens's story has since been dramatised on film, including in *Race* (2016).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1936-summer-olympics] The Berlin Games are now widely cited as the archetypal example of "sportswashing"—the use of a prestigious sporting event to improve the image of an authoritarian government—and as a precedent in debates over later host selections.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After Japan declared in 1938 that it would be unable to host the 1940 Olympics in Tokyo due to the ongoing Second Sino-Japanese War, Helsinki had been selected to host the 1940 Summer Olympics, which were then cancelled due to World War II.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo eventually hosted the games in 1964.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki is the northernmost city at which a summer Olympic Games have been held.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With London hosting the 1948 Olympics, 1952 is the most recent time when two consecutive summer Olympic Games were held entirely in Europe.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Summer Olympics was the last of the two consecutive Olympics to be held in Northern Europe, following the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo, Norway.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] They were also the Olympic Games at which the most world records were broken until they were surpassed by the 2008 Summer Games in Beijing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Bahamas, Guatemala, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Israel, Netherlands Antilles, Nigeria, the People's Republic of China, Saarland, the Soviet Union, Thailand, and Vietnam made their Olympic debuts at the 1952 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States won the most gold and overall medals at these Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Inspired by the success of the Swedish 1912 Olympics, Finnish sports fans began to arouse the idea of their own Olympic Games: for example, Erik von Frenckell publicly presented his dreams of the Finnish Olympic Games at the opening of the 1915 Töölön Pallokenttä.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As the Olympic success continued in the 1920s, enthusiasm for one's own Olympics grew, and after the 1920 Antwerp Olympics, Finnish sports leaders began planning to build a stadium in Helsinki in 1920.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finland's main sports organizations and the City of Helsinki founded the Stadion Foundation in 1927 to get the stadium to Helsinki.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the same year, Ernst Edvard Krogius, who represented Finland on the International Olympic Committee (IOC), announced Finland's willingness to host the competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1930, preparations for the 1936 Games, which was accelerated by the launch of a design project for the Olympic Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Helsinki was not a candidate in the first round in 1931, and Berlin won the competition, but Helsinki immediately registered as a candidate for the 1940 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] World War II broke out on 1 September 1939, with the German–Soviet invasion of Poland, which also drew Britain and France to war.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Despite the aggression, the Organizing Committee of the Olympic Games continued to be optimistic about the preparations for the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the Soviet invasion of Finland on 30 November 1939, halted planning for the games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the Winter War, the Organizing Committee decided to abandon the Games on 20 March 1940 due to the hostilities across Europe, the suspension of preparations caused by the Winter War, and the deplorable economic situation.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the meeting of the Finnish Olympic Committee on 20 April 1940, the Olympic Games in Finland were officially canceled.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the meantime, World War II had already expanded, with Germany occupying Denmark and fighting in Norway.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Instead of the Olympic Games, Finland held a Memorial Competitions for Fallen Athletes who died in the Winter War against Russia, at the opening of which actor Eino Kaipainen recited the poem *Silent Winners* written by Yrjö Jylhä.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The memorial competitions were held on the initiative of the sports journalist Sulo Kolkka.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of World War II, London was awarded the 1948 Summer Olympics after the city was originally granted the 1944 Games, which were canceled due to the war.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki continued its attempt to have the Games organized and registered as candidates for the 1952 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the IOC Congress in Stockholm on 21 June 1947, Helsinki was chosen as the host city, leaving behind the bids of Amsterdam, Los Angeles, Minneapolis, Detroit, Chicago and Philadelphia.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki's strengths included the fairly completed venues built for the 1940 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After confirmation that Helsinki would host the Games, the "XV Olympia Helsinki 1952" was established as the organizing committee of the Games on 8 September 1947.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Its members were the Finnish Olympic Committee, the Finnish State, the City of Helsinki and 26 various sports organizations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The mayor of Helsinki Erik von Frenckell was elected chairman of the committee, who at the time also chaired Finnish Football Association.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Akseli Kaskela, Olavi Suvanto and Armas-Eino Martola were elected Vice-Chairs.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Among them, Kaskela and Suvanto were elected on political grounds as representatives of the bourgeois Finnish Sports Federation (SVUL) and the leftist Finnish Workers' Sports Federation (TUL), Martola, on the other hand, got a former officer to lead the organization of the practical arrangements.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Other members of the Organizing Committee were Yrjö Enne, Väinö A.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Karikoski, Urho Kekkonen, Ernst Krogius, William Lehtinen, Aarne K.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Leskinen, Eino Pekkala, Väinö Salovaara and Erik Åström.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1948–1949, Karikoski, Kekkonen, Krogius and Lehtinen resigned from the committee, and Lauri Miettinen, Arno Tuurna and Yrjö Valkama were elected to replace them.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the spring of 1952, Ente was replaced by Arvi E.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Heiskanen and as completely new members by Mauno Pekkala and Aaro Tynell.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Erik von Frenckell was the chairman of the organizing committee and the other members were Armas-Eino Martola (competition director), Yrjö Valkama (sports director), Olavi Suvanto (maintenance director), Akseli Kaskela, Aarne K.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, the head of the central office Kallio Kotkas and the head of information Eero Petäjäniemi were involved in the competition organization.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The international political atmosphere was tense when the Helsinki Olympics were held.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When the IOC held its meeting in Vienna in 1951, many difficult topics were on the agenda.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Cold War was under way, and the situation between Israel and Arab countries, divided Germany had to be addressed as a team, and the Chinese Civil War, with the Chinese Communist Party winning, forming the People's Republic of China and the Republic of China government exiled to Taiwan.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Four years earlier, Japan was not invited to the London Olympics from the losing states of the Second World War.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic Committee of Israel had not yet been recognized, and a successor to the German Olympic Committee, which had been dissolved during World War II, had not yet been established, but all these countries already participated in the Helsinki Games, as did Saarland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Cold War affected the participation of both the United States and the Soviet Union in the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The participation of the United States in the Games was decided only after the country had received an assessment of the political situation in Finland from its embassy in Helsinki.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union was accepted as a member of the IOC in May 1951, and in December of the same year the country accepted the invitation to the competition, as the country's athletes were in medal condition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Although the Soviet leadership had previously considered the Games a bourgeois event, the Helsinki Games held propaganda value.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the Soviet Union, billions of rubles were spent on coaching athletes in just one year.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union planned to fly its athletes every day between Leningrad and Helsinki.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Another option was for Soviet athletes to stay in the Soviet Porkkalanniemi garrison.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Finland required that all competitors stay in the Olympic village.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As a compromise solution for the Eastern Bloc athletes, a second Olympic village was established in Espoo, Otaniemi as Soviet leaders wanted them to avoid contact with Western athletes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Joseph Stalin allowed Soviet athletes to enter the 1952 Summer Olympics because he was sure that they would win the most medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, American athletes secured more gold and total medals and Stalin afforded more resources for the advancement of elite athletes in the Soviet Union in the build-up to the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Games were also threatened with cancellation due to the deteriorating world situation.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Korean War had begun in 1950, which also caused concern in the organizing committee.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At Von Frenckell's suggestion, the organizing committee decided to take out Lloyd's of London war insurance.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Most of the venues for the competitions were completed prior to the 1940s in anticipation of successful bid attempts, but some expansion and refurbishment work was needed, including the construction of additional stands at the Olympic and Swimming Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A residential area, Kisakylä (Olympic Village) was built south of Käpylä's Koskelantie to accommodate competitors.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The area, which was built close to the 1940 Olympics, was already the residence of the people of Helsinki at that time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Just below the opening, the competition area was completed for the use of visitors Kumpula Outdoor Swimming Pool.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Female athletes got their own race village from the Nursing College in Meilahti.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The athletes of the Soviet-led Eastern Bloc stayed in the Teekkarikylä in Otaniemi.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Finnish team lived on the premises of the Santahamina Army School (later the Cadet School, now the National Defence University).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The City of Helsinki prepared for the Olympics by building a new airport in Seutula (now Helsinki-Vantaan lentoasema), 11-story Hotelli Palace, and the Olympic Pier in South Harbor.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A large electric scoreboard was procured.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It attracted international attention because it represented the top of its time in the scoreboard field both in terms of its system and its technology.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] OMEGA debuted the OMEGA Time Recorder in Helsinki.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This all-new quartz clock not only timed the events but also printed out the results.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This breakthrough technology allowed official Olympic times to be accurate to 1/100 of a second.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] As a result, the company received the prestigious Croix du Mérite Olympique award for their efforts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In 1950 cable television was tried for the first time in Finland, in the 1952 Olympics people could watch TV sending from the stadium through coaxial cable to Stockmann department store window.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki paved tens of kilometers of roads, and a myriad of houses were painted.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The city's first traffic lights were installed at the intersection of Aleksanterinkatu and Mikonkatu in October 1951.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Palace Hotel and Vaakuna Hotel among others, were completed for the needs of the guests.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, due to the relatively low number of hotels in the city, tent villages were built for tourists in Lauttasaari and Seurasaari, among others.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the preparations for accommodation turned out to be considerably oversized; at its best, the occupancy rate of the 6,000-seat tent village in Lauttasaari had an occupancy of only 8 per cent.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With the support of the Olympia 1952 committee, Finland's first mini golf courses were completed to entertain guests.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The International Olympic Committee had declared in 1950 that it did not have an official Olympic anthem, but that the organizers could decide their own anthems.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] An anthem competition was held in Finland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the spring of 1951, a poetry competition was announced, which was surprisingly won by an unknown teacher candidate, Niilo Partanen.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Second and third came the well-known poets Toivo Lyy and Heikki Asunta.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] These winning poems were allowed to be used in the composition competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The selection of the 51 compositions by a jury chaired by Jouko Tolonen was also a surprise.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When the winner was announced on 17 March 1952, an unknown teacher Jaakko Linjama was revealed behind the nickname, who had used Lyy's lyrics in his Olympic Hymn.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The nicknames of the other contestants were not opened.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] This caused a stir, and Arijoutsi, among others, doubted that the victory of the unknown would go to the honor of well-known composers.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were well-known members in the competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The voters had identified the composing style of Uuno Klami and Aarre Merikanto, among others.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The only Finnish composer who congratulated Linjamaa was Jean Sibelius, who did not take part in the anthem.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch was transported by land from Olympia to Athens from where fire's journey continued in a miner's lamp donated by the Saar Olympic Committee on a SAS plane to Aalborg, Denmark.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The glass cover surrounding the lamp was designed by the artist Sakari Tohka.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch itself was designed by the artist Aukusti Tuhka.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] From Denmark, the torchlight continued by running, cycling, riding, rowing and paddling to Copenhagen, from where the fire was transported by ferry to Sweden to Malmö.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The journey of the torch across Sweden was carried to Haparanda by 700 messengers, from where it continued to the Finnish side in Tornio.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the Finnish-Swedish border bridge, the torch was received by Ville Pörhölä, who brought it to Tornio sports ground.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch from Tornio, Greece, was connected to Pallastunturi on 6 July 1952 where it ignited the "midnight sun fire".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In reality, the Pallastunturi fire was lit with liquefied petroleum gas, because the night in July was cloudy at that time and it was not possible to use the sun as a lighter.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] From Tornio, the torch traveled through Finland to Helsinki.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It was transported by more than 1,200 people.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, the aim was to transport fire to Helsinki via the Soviet Union, but the matter was not settled through diplomacy by the deadline.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The journey covered a total of 7,870 kilometres on the journey that began on 25 June and ended on 19 July 1952.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The actual Olympic flame was lit for the Olympic Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony of the Helsinki Olympics was held on 19 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Although the weather was rainy and chilly and the Olympic Stadium had no roof but on top of the main auditorium, the stadium was full with 70,435 spectators.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The inaugural march had a record 5,469 people from 67 countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the march, the countries organized themselves into the central lawn, and the chairman of the organizing committee, Erik von Frenckell, spoke in Finnish, Swedish, French and English.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Paasikivi gave the opening speech, which was the shortest in Olympic history and contained a mistake: it was not the "Fifteenth Olympic Games", but the XV Olympic Games and the 12th World Olympics, due to the 1916, 1940 and 1944 races had been canceled.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The speech was followed by the raising of the Olympic flag and the *Olympic fanfare* composed by Aarre Merikanto.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic flame was lit by running heroes Paavo Nurmi (to the stadium) and Hannes Kolehmainen (to the stadium tower).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] When Paavo Nurmi was announced to arrive at the stadium, athletes from the participating countries deviated from the formation to see the legend better.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Only the lines of the Soviet Union and Finland remained in the line.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] After the Olympic flame was lit, the Archbishop Ilmari Salomies was due to say a prayer, but German Barbara Rotbraut-Pleyer, nicknamed "White Angel of the Games", had jumped from the auditorium onto the track and ran straight to the speaker's seat.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Organizers quickly removed Pleyer, who had time to say just a few words into the microphone.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Pleyer's purpose was to proclaim a message of peace.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Heikki Savolainen, a gymnast who was competing in his fifth consecutive Olympic games, swore the Olympic oath on behalf of the athletes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 4,925 athletes from 69 countries, with the Soviet Union making its Olympic debut and Germany participating for the first time since World War II.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 149 events were held in 17 different sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most-medalling athletes of the Games were Viktor Chukarin of the Soviet Union, who won four gymnastics Olympic gold medals, and Czechoslovakia's Emil Zátopek, who won three track golds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States won the most gold and total medals, with 40 and 76.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The host country, Finland, had 6 gold, 3 silver and 13 bronze medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Shooting was competed in seven events, six of which (rifle sports) were conducted at the Malmi Shooting Range in moderately difficult wind conditions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Tough results were still fired in Helsinki, as the top four deer shooting broke world records.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] World records for knee position were also broken in free and small rifles.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Shotgun shooting took place at the Huopalahti shooting range.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Ten countries took medals from the shooting.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Norway was the only country to win two gold medals, with the Soviet Union winning the most medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Boris Andreyev was the only Soviet shooter to win two multiple medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A Finnish winner was already celebrated in a miniature rifle when Vilho Ylönen had time to play on the radio *Björneborgarnas marsch*.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, in an hour-long countdown, the Norwegian Erling Asbjørn Kongshaug was declared the winner of the competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The football tournament started even before the official opening, as the one-piece qualifiers took place on 15–16 July in Kotka, Lahti, Tampere, Turku and Helsinki.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 27 countries registered for the tournament, but Saarland and Mexico dropped out before the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary *Golden Team* won the gold when it knocked down the Yugoslavia in the final with a score of 2–0.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the final, the Olympic Stadium had 58 553 paid spectators, the largest number of spectators in Finland watching a football match.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The first meeting between the Soviet Union and Yugoslavia in football is still amongst the most famous matches.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the political level, the Soviet leader Joseph Stalin and the Yugoslav leader Josip Tito split in 1948, which resulted in Yugoslavia being excluded from the Communist Information Bureau.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The origin of the conflict was Tito's refusal to submit to Stalin's interpretations and visions of politics and in process becoming a Soviet satellite state.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Before the match, both Tito and Stalin sent telegrams to their national teams, which showed just how important it was for the two head of states.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Yugoslavia led 5–1, but a Soviet comeback in the last 15 minutes resulted in a 5–5 draw.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The match was replayed, Yugoslavia winning 3–1.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The defeat to the archrivals hit Soviet football hard, and after just three games played in the season, CSKA Moscow, who had made up most of the USSR squad, was forced to withdraw from the league by Joseph Stalin and later disbanded.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Furthermore, Boris Arkadiev, who coached both USSR and CDKA, was stripped of his Merited Master of Sports of the USSR title.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] 23 teams entered basketball, ten of which made it directly to the actual tournament.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The remaining 13 countries took the final six places in the Olympic tournament before the official opening of the Olympic Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In basketball, the gold medal was won by the United States, who defeated Soviet Union in the final 36–25.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The final match was relatively slow-paced, as the Soviet Union tried to keep up with the United States by freezing the game.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States had already clearly beat the Soviet Union 86–58 earlier in the tournament.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze was won by Uruguay, who also organized a mass battle after being dissatisfied with the referee's work.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Field hockey was included in the Helsinki Olympic Games in the range of sports on the condition that a maximum of 12 teams register for the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the end, 16 teams applied for the competition, from which the International Field Hockey Federation selected 12 countries to participate in the competition venue.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Eventually, four countries dropped out of the Games, so the remaining 12 teams that had applied for the competition were able to take part in the Olympic tournament.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The tournament started with two rounds before the Games opened, and the final match was held on 24 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] India and Netherlands met in the Velodrome final, with India winning its fifth consecutive gold under captaincy of Kunwar Digvijay Singh with a score of 6–1.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Canoeing competitions were held Taivallahti 27–28 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were a total of 159 participants in eight men's and women's only races, coming from 21 countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Canoeing was a celebration in Finland, as four of the nine sports went to the host country.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, the Finns took one silver and a bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The double gold medalists were Kurt Wires and Yrjö Hietanen who won the kayak duo's 1,000 and 10,000 meters.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the only women's sport, the 500-meter kayak unit, gold was taken by Sylvi Saimo, who was the first Finnish female gold medalist in the summer competitions.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The second most successful country in kayaking was Sweden, which won one gold and three silver.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Helsinki Olympics fencing competitions were held on the Espoo side of the Westend Tennis Hall.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The men competed with Épée, sabre and foil in both personal competition and team competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The women had only a personal competition for foil in the program.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were 250 men and 37 women from 32 countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Italy, Hungary and France were, as usual, the best fencing countries and took all the gold medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of six countries reached medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Mangiarot brothers Edoardo and Dario took a double victory over the film.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungarian swordsmen won a triple victory over the preserve.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Modern pentathlon Olympic competitions was held at Ahvenisto Hämeenlinna.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 51 competitors from 19 countries entered the sport.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, the sport also included a team competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden, Hungary and Finland shared the medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden's Lars Hall won the individual competition, and Hungary was the best in the team competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Before Hall, all Olympic winners of the sport have been officers.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, Hall was a carpenter by profession.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Töölö Sports Hall held Olympic boxing between 28 July to 2 August in ten weight classes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most successful boxing country was the United States, which won five gold.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union won the most medals, but its boxers did not win a single championship.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the middle series, the American Floyd Patterson knocked out Romanian Vasile Tiță in a record-breaking 42 seconds.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The American Norvel Lee, who won the heavyweight series, was awarded as the most technical boxer in the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the heavyweight series Ed Sanders got gold when the Swedish Ingemar Johansson was rejected for his passivity.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Johansson did not receive his silver medal until 1982.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Wrestling was held in Helsinki in eight weight classes in both Greco-Roman wrestling and freestyle wrestling.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] All finals were held in the larger Exhibition Hall I, but freestyle wrestling events were held in the smaller Exhibition Hall II.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Free button competitions were held on 20–23 July, and Greco-Roman wrestling matches took place on 24–27 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most successful wrestling country was the Soviet Union, whose athletes won six gold and a total of ten medals in the sport.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Sweden dominated free wrestling and received the second highest number of medals in wrestling overall.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The overwhelming athlete in wrestling was the Soviet Johannes Kotkas, who competed in the heavy series of Greco-Roman wrestling.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] He managed to beat all his opponents in less than five minutes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic weightlifting competition was held in seven weight classes with 141 competitors.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, there were to be only six weight classes, but a light heavyweight series was also added to the program, as a result of which the weight limit for the heavyweight series increased from 82.5 kilograms to 90 kilograms.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The addition of the new weight class took place so late that there was no time to change the race program.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Weightlifting was carried out according to plan at the Exhibition Hall on 25–27 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] All seven gold medals were awarded to athletes from the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviets won a total of seven medals, but the Americans took four championships, while the Soviets only took three.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of five world records were set in weightlifting.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the heavyweight series John Davis continued his superiority, Davis had not lost a single event since 1938 and continued with his victory in Helsinki as well.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The competition took place in the waters of Helsinki from 20 to 28 May in five different categories.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Larger boats sailed in front of Harmaja lighthouse island, and the Finn race was held near Liuskasaari.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 93 crews from 29 countries took part in the competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States, Norway and Sweden took three medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States was the only country to reach two gold medals in sailing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the Finn that developed from the Firefly class, the Danish Paul Elvstrøm won the overwhelming championship.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The gold medal was the second in Elvstrøm's career.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] He later became the first athlete to win the same sport four times in a row (individual disciplines).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In cycling, medals were awarded in six sports, four for track cycling and two for road racing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In total, 214 competitors from 36 countries took part in the cycling.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Track cycling competitions were held from 29 to 31 July and road driving on 2 August.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of seven countries collected medals and gold medals went to Italy, Australia and Belgium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Italy was the most successful country with five medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Two gold medals went to Australian Russell Mockridge, who won the championship in the kilometer time trial and with his partner in tandem racing, and the Belgian André Noyelle, who won the 190 kilometer road race personal competition and team competition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Equestrian events were competed in dressage, Eventing and show jumping in person and in team competition in a total of six sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Eight countries won medals in horseback riding, and Sweden was by far the most successful country.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Swedes won both races in both dressage and field riding.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] For the events in first time non-military officers including women were allowed to take part in dressage events in Helsinki.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In a show jumping, Danish Lis Hartel, paralyzed from her knees down, was the first woman to win a riding medal after finishing second in the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Rowers competed in seven sports from 20 to 23 July.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The competition was held in Meilahti, as Taivallahti, where the canoeing competitions took place, was too open to the sea breeze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] There were a total of 409 entrants from 33 countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Representatives from fourteen countries won medals, and only American rowers won two gold medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The youngest Olympic winner of the Games was seen in Rowing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the coxswain duo, the French winning team included 14 years old Bernard Malivoire.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Diving competed in a total of four men's and women's events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The United States led the events, as nine of the 12 medals in the distribution went to the country.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In addition to the United States, only France, Mexico and Germany won medals in the sport.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Patricia McCormick won Olympic gold in the women's events from both the three-meter springboard and the ten-meter floor jump.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] At the Helsinki Swimming Stadium men competed in six sports and women in five sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] High-level competitions were held from July 25 to 2 August.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Summer Olympics in London had resulted in significant progress in the sport, and every Olympic record was broken in each event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Americans dominated men's events and the Hungarians dominated women.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Ford Konno was the most successful swimmer with two gold medals and one silver.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the women's events Katalin Szőke won two gold medals and Éva Novák two silver in addition to the gold medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The only world record in the Games was set by the Hungarian women's 4 × 100 meter freestyle message team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Helsinki Olympics, was the last instance where competitors could participate in Breaststroke in the butterfly stroke.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the men's events, no athlete swimming in the breaststroke style made it to the finals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 21 countries took part in the water polo tournament.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The initial series of the Games was to be played in the offshore pools, but due to the coolness of the water, the International Swimming Federation ordered all the matches to be played at the Swimming Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Because of this, some of the matches in the first series had to be played as early as six in the morning.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The water polo championship was decided in the final block, where the four teams faced each other once.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary and Yugoslavia ended in a draw after winning two other matches and playing 2–2 each other.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Hungary won gold with a better goal difference.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 1952 Olympic gymnastics was dominated by the Soviet Union, which had already been an established gymnastics power by 1952.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The USSR's athletes won nine gold medals and took a total of 22 medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finland, Germany and Switzerland, who previously dominated the gymnastics at the Olympics, were content with more modest success.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of fifteen medals were awarded, eight in men's events and seven in women's events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The most personal medals in gymnastics were taken by Viktor Chukarin in the men's events and Maria Gorokhovskaya in the women's events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Gorokhovskaya won medals in every women's sport.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Her seven-medal catch (two gold and five silver) was a record for one women's Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Athletics was competed in 33 sports, 24 for men and 9 for women.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] By far the most successful state was the United States, which won 31 medals, nine of which were gold.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union reached 17 medals, but won only two championships, and the eight-medal country Germany was left without first places.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The second medalist was Czechoslovakia, with four of the five medals being the brightest.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Emil Zátopek won the 5,000 and 10,000 meters, as well as the marathon, which he had never run before, all in new Olympic record times.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] On the women's side, the Australian Marjorie Jackson won the 100 and 200 meter runs.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the triple jump Adhemar Ferreira da Silva broke the old world record four times.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the decathlon, Bob Mathias made a new ME and took the victory with a total score of 7,887 points, more than 900 points to the next.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Josy Barthel of Luxembourg pulled a major surprise by winning the 1500 m.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] According to the Olympic rules, the organizer of the Games was allowed to choose between two types of demonstration sports, one from abroad and one from Finland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In connection with the Helsinki Games, a handball and pesäpallo (Finnish baseball) match was held.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the handball match of the Games, Sweden and Denmark faced at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The level of playing outside was modest due to heavy rain.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The pesäpallo match was also played at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Finnish Baseball Federation and Finnish Workers' Sports Federation teams competed in the event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Baseball Federation won the match 8–4.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] During the breaks in both shows, the audience was entertained by the performances of Finnish male and female gymnasts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] With an annual average temperature of 5.9 °C (42.6 °F), Helsinki is one of the coldest cities to have hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Most of the competition venues were located in Helsinki Metropolitan Area.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Modern pentathlon and some field hockey games were held in Hämeenlinna and some football games by Tampere, Lahti, Kotka and Turku.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The main arena was the Olympic Stadium, which hosted the opening and closing ceremonies, athletics competitions, football semi-finals and finals, as well as the show jumping competition "Prix des Nations" were held.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The stadium was built for the 1940 Olympics and opened as early as 1938, but had suffered under the bombing of World War II.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] It had to undergo expansion and refurbishment work.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The concrete auditorium section was expanded and a new temporary wooden auditorium was built on the south and north curves and on the east side, which increased the Stadium's audience capacity to about 70,000.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The swimming competitions were held at Helsinki Swimming Stadium, located just a few hundred meters east of the Olympic Stadium and with three pools: a racing, diving and children's pool.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The swimming stadium could accommodate about 9,500 spectators, while the wooden eastern and standing stands for the Games could accommodate a total of about 6,000 people.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Fair Hall near the stadiums (now Töölö Sports Hall) many of the indoor events were held in two separate halls.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In the bigger hall, men competed in gymnastics, wrestling and boxing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The smaller hall hosts the women's gymnastics, freestyle wrestling, weightlifting and basketball finals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Basketball first round matches were played at Tennis Palace and fencing competitions were held at the Westend tennis center in Espoo.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The shooting events took place at the Malmi shooting range 11 kilometers from the center of Helsinki, with the exception of clay pigeon shooting.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Clay pigeon shooting was performed on the Finnish Hunters' Association track Huopalahti.Ruskeasuo competed in dressage as well as in Tali and Laakso in field riding.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Töölö Rowing Stadium was built for rowing and canoeing events one kilometer from Taivallahti.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] However, the place was not accepted as a place for rowing competitions, as it was open to the sea breeze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The rowing took place in Meilahti about three kilometers from the Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The place was considerably more sheltered than Taivallahti.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Harmaja, a lighthouse island a couple of kilometers off the coast of Helsinki, was the starting and finishing area for larger sailing classes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Finn was the starting and finish point of the race Liuskasaari close to the coast.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Marathon running route was north of the Stadium to Käpylä, Pakinkylä, Tuomarinkylä, Vantaa, Tikkurila and Korso.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] In Tuusula, Mätäkivenmäki there was a turning point from which the runners set off on their way back to the Stadium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 50-kilometer walk was organized along the same route.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A memorial stone was later erected at the turning point along Old Tuusulantie.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A swimming stadium was built in Hämeenlinna for Ahvenisto for the pentathlon.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The other four pentathlon events were also held in the vicinity of Ahvenisto.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 69 nations participated in these Games, up from 59 in the 1948 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Thirteen nations made their first Olympic appearance in 1952: The Bahamas, the People's Republic of China, Gold Coast (now Ghana), Guatemala, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Israel, Netherlands Antilles, Nigeria, the Soviet Union (USSR), Thailand, and Vietnam.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Japan and Germany were both reinstated and permitted to send athletes after being banned for 1948 for their instigation of World War II.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Due to the division of Germany, German athletes from Saar entered a separate team for the only time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Only West Germany would provide athletes for the actual German team, since East Germany refused to participate in a joint German team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Romania returned to the games in this edition.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Nations that participated in the previous games in London 1948 but were absent in Helsinki 1952 included Afghanistan, Colombia, Malta, Peru and Syria.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Bahamas, Bermuda, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Nigeria, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] Netherlands Antilles was a constituent country of the Kingdom of Netherlands.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union sent the largest delegation.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1952 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The 50th anniversary of the Helsinki Olympic Games was the main motif for one of the first Finnish euro silver commemorative coins, the €10 silver coin minted in 2002.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The reverse depicts part of the Helsinki Olympic Stadium, as well as a section of the 1952 500 markka coin.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p01] The obverse has lettering SUOMI FINLAND 10 EURO, a flame, and Finland is the only country highlighted on Earth.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In total 2,394,099 admission tickets were printed for the Helsinki games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] About two million of them were made Bank of Finland banknote printing works.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] To prevent counterfeiting, tickets were printed on watermark banknote paper.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Printing began in July 1951 and lasted four months.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In early 1952, the race organizers opened their own ticket offices for sales at home and abroad.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Half of the more than two million admission tickets were put up for sale abroad.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, only about 250,000 tickets were sold.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, foreign tourists also bought a lot of tickets from Finland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] A total of 1,376,512 tickets were sold for various competition events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] There were four different price categories.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Prices varied between 300 and 2,100 FIM, which in current currency corresponds to about 9–65 euros.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Ticket revenue totaled approximately FIM 965 million, or EUR 29.7 million.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Entrance tickets were printed in ten different colors, depending on the venue and the auditorium.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Except for the color, the flags were all similar in appearance.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The texts in Finnish, Swedish, English and French were printed on them, and the sport was also indicated by a symbol in the upper left corner.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] A spectator map was printed on the back of the entrance tickets.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Tickets sold to Finland only marked their Price Category, foreign tickets also marked the price US Dollars.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In addition to tickets made by the organizers, the City of Hämeenlinna printed its own entry tickets for modern pentathlon competitions held locally.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] They were simpler in design than other tickets.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics influenced the Finns, the City of Helsinki and the image of foreigners.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics can even be considered a symbolic decision for the post-war years in Finland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Reconstruction of the land was practically completed in 1952, although at the beginning of the decade many had lived in temporary housing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The last war reparations was paid in September 1952, and regulatory policy was abolished at the same time.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] On the closing day of the Games, 3 August 1952, President J.K.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Paasikivi wrote in his diary: "The Olympics were a great success.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Foreigners, including the magazines, have praised the good organization.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Helsinki cityscape was clearly a new impetus for the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The development of Helsinki had already begun in the late 1930s, when Parliament House, Lasipalatsi and Pääposti were built.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Olympic dreams motivate many construction projects.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Helsinki's entertainment and nightlife was modest compared to previous race hosts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Many temporary restaurants and entertainment venues were set up in the city for the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The city had been planning a fair for decades, but even for this project, the Olympic host gave the final impetus.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] After the competition was confirmed, the city of Helsinki started looking for a place for an amusement park in Alppila.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Linnanmäki Amusement Park was opened on 27 May 1950 on a plot leased in December 1949.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympics also developed Helsinki's infrastructure with the construction of a new airport, Olympic Pier, new asphalt and the city's first traffic lights.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympic spirit was also visible outside the capital region.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In 1952, Finland's first rest stop for motorists was opened in Lahnajärvi, along the former Highway 1 (current road 110).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The impact of the Olympics on Finns is difficult to define.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] It was certainly good for Finns' self-confidence to create a successful major event together and at the same time get a new kind of contact with the interaction between peoples.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For the first time, many Finns were in contact with non-Caucasian foreigners at the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] At the same time, the Olympics united Finns in their disputes.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For example, Finnish Workers' Sports Federation and Finnish Sports Federation strong disputes between were on a break during the Olympics, even though they continued even after the Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] With internationalization, new products also arrived in Finland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The best known of these is Coca-Cola (Coca-Cola arrived in Finland as early as the 1930s through Stockmann).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In addition, chewing gum was imported for the first time, and Alko launched new drinks, including Gin Long Drink.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] Finland's relations with United Kingdom clearly warmed up thanks to the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] This was particularly influenced by the fact that Prince Philip, who came to visit the Games, received a warm welcome in Finland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] After the Second World War, Britain had been rude to Finland, but the Olympics showed that Finland belonged to the Western world.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In Finland, the Helsinki Olympics are sometimes called the last real Olympics, when trying to emphasize the nature of the Games as the last Games of the true Olympic spirit, a sporting and non-commercial event.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] For example, a book about competitions written by Antero Raevuori is named after this saying.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However, the phrase was invented in Finland and is not used elsewhere in the world.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] It was developed at the turn of the 1970s and 1980s, when doping began to become more widespread in sports, 1972 Summer Olympics the Munich massacre, and the 1976, 1980 and 1984 the Summer Olympics were widely boycotted.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] In a way, the Helsinki Olympics were a return to smaller competitions due to resources, as Finland is the smallest country to host the Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] However the 1956 Summer Olympics involved fewer participating athletes than in Helsinki, and in practice it was not until the 1970s that the Games clearly began to expand.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Helsinki Olympics were still relatively non-commercial, although the Polish press, for example, barked at the Helsinki Olympics as "competitions for disgusting traders".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1952-summer-olympics-p02] The Helsinki Games were also not much smaller in terms of marketing than the following Games, and marketing was well known in the Olympic world with Kodak supporting the Games as far back as the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at these Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to be staged in the Southern Hemisphere and Oceania, as well as the first to be held outside Europe and North America.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne is the most southerly city ever to host the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Australia hosted the Games for a second time in 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, and will host them again in 2032 in Brisbane, Queensland.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic equestrian events could not be held in Melbourne due to Australia's strict quarantine regulations, so they were held in Stockholm five months earlier.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] This was the second time the Olympics were not held entirely in one country, the first being the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium, with some events taking place in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Despite uncertainties and various complications encountered during the preparations, the 1956 Games went ahead in Melbourne as planned and turned out to be a success.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Started during the 1956 Games was the "Parade of Athletes" at the closing ceremonies.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Nine teams boycotted the Games for various reasons.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon) boycotted in response to the Suez Crisis, in which Egypt was invaded by Israel, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (the Netherlands, Spain, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) boycotted in response to the Soviet invasion of Hungary, and the People's Republic of China's boycott was in response to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] One of the most notable events of the games was a controversial water polo match between the Soviet Union and the defending champions, Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had recently suppressed an anti-authoritarian revolution in Hungary and violence broke out between the teams during the match, resulting in numerous injuries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] When Hungary's Ervin Zádor suffered bleeding after being punched by the Soviet Union's Valentin Prokopov, spectators attempted to join the violence, but they were blocked by police.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The match was cancelled, with Hungary being declared the winner because they were in the lead 4–0.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected as the host city over bids from Buenos Aires, Mexico City, Montreal, Los Angeles, Detroit, Chicago, Minneapolis, Philadelphia, and San Francisco at the 43rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy on 28 April 1949.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Mexico City, Montreal and Los Angeles would eventually be selected to host the 1968, 1976 and 1984 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Many members of the IOC were skeptical about Melbourne as an appropriate site.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Its location in the Southern Hemisphere was a major concern since the reversal of seasons would mean the Games must be held during the northern winter.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The November–December schedule was thought likely to inconvenience athletes from the Northern Hemisphere, who were accustomed to resting during their winter.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Notwithstanding these concerns, the field of candidates eventually narrowed to two Southern Hemisphere cities, these being Melbourne and Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected, in 1949, to host the 1956 Olympics by a one-vote margin.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The first sign of trouble was the revelation that Australian equine quarantine would prevent the country from hosting the equestrian events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Stockholm was selected as the alternative site, so equestrian competition began on 10 June, five and a half months before the rest of the Olympic Games were to open.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The above problems of the Melbourne Games were compounded by bickering over financing among Australian politicians.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Eventually, in March 1953, the State Government accepted a £2 million loan from the Commonwealth Government to build the Olympic Village, which would accommodate up to 6,000 people, in Heidelberg West.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] After the Olympics, the houses in the village were handed back to the Housing Commission for general public housing.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] At one point, IOC President Avery Brundage suggested that Rome, which was to host the 1960 Games, was so far ahead of Melbourne in preparations that it might be ready as a replacement site in 1956.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Constructing of the sporting venues was given priority over the athlete's village.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The village was designed as a whole new suburb with semi-detached houses and flats, the first village that both sexes could cohabitate the same buildings instead of gender designated sections.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] As late as April 1955, Brundage, who was presiding over the Olympics for the first time, was still doubtful about Melbourne and was not satisfied by an inspection trip to the city.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Construction was well under way by then, thanks to a $4.5 million federal loan to Victoria, but it was behind schedule.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] He still held out the possibility that Rome might have to step in.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] By the beginning of 1956, though, it was obvious that Melbourne would be ready for the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon announced that they would not participate in the Olympics in response to the Suez Crisis when Egypt was invaded by Israel, the United Kingdom, and France.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The Netherlands, Spain, Switzerland and Liechtenstein boycotted the event in protest of the Soviet Union's crushing of the Hungarian Revolution.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The People's Republic of China chose to boycott the event because Taiwan had been allowed to compete.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from both East and West Germany competed together as a combined team (a display of unity that was repeated in 1960 and 1964, but was then discontinued).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Although the number of countries participating (67) was almost the same as in 1952 (69), the number of athletes competing dropped sharply, from 4,925 to 3,342.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Once underway, the Games progressed smoothly, and came to be known as the "Friendly Games".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Betty Cuthbert, an 18-year-old from Sydney, won the 100 and 200 metre sprint races and ran an exceptional final leg in the 4 x 100 metre relay to overcome Great Britain's lead and claim her third gold medal, becoming known as the "Golden Girl".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The veteran Shirley Strickland repeated her 1952 win in the 80 metre hurdles and was also part of the winning 4 x 100 metre relay team, bringing her career Olympic medal total to seven: three golds, a silver, and three bronze medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] They won all of the freestyle races, men's and women's, and collected a total of eight gold, four silver and two bronze medals.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Murray Rose became the first male swimmer to win two freestyle events (and a total three events) since Johnny Weissmuller in 1924, while Dawn Fraser won gold medals in the 100 metre freestyle and as the leadoff swimmer in the 4 x 100 metre relay team.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The men's track and field events were dominated by the United States.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] They not only won 15 of the 24 events, they swept four of them and took first and second place in five others.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Bobby Morrow led the way with gold medals in the 100 and 200 metre sprints and the 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Tom Courtney barely overtook Great Britain's Derek Johnson in the 800 metre run, then collapsed from the exertion and needed medical attention.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Ireland's Ronnie Delany ran an outstanding 53.8 over the last 400 metres to win the 1,500 metre run (also Ireland's last gold medal in track events), in which favourite John Landy of Australia finished third.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] There was a major upset, marred briefly by controversy, in the 3,000 metre steeplechase.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Little-known Chris Brasher of Great Britain finished well ahead of the field, but the judges disqualified him for interfering with Norway's Ernst Larsen, and they announced Sándor Rozsnyói of Hungary as the winner.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Brasher's appeal was supported by Larsen, Rozsnyói, and fourth-place finisher Heinz Laufer of Germany.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Subsequently, the decision was reversed and Brasher became the first Briton to win a gold medal in track and field since 1936.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Soviet runner Vladimir Kuts won two golds by winning both the 5,000-metre and 10,000-metre events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Only two world records were set in track and field.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Mildred McDaniel, the first American woman to win gold in the sport, set a high jump record of 1.76 metres (5.8 ft), and Egil Danielsen of Norway overcame blustery conditions with a remarkable javelin throw of 85.71 metres (281.2 ft).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Throughout the Olympics, Hungarian athletes were cheered by fans from Australia and other countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Many of them gathered in the boxing arena when thirty-year-old Laszlo Papp of Hungary won a record third gold medal by beating José Torres for the light-middleweight championship.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] A few days later, the crowd was with the Hungarian water polo team in its hotly contested and emotionally charged match against the Soviet Union which took place against the background of the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The game became rough and, when a Hungarian was forced to leave the pool with a bleeding wound above his eye, a riot almost broke out.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The police restored order and the game was called early, with Hungary leading 4–0, and the Hungarians went on to win the gold medal.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] In a much publicized Olympic romance, American hammer throw champion Hal Connolly would marry Czechoslovak discus throw champion, Olga Fikotová.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] After moving to the United States, Olga wanted to continue representing Czechoslovakia, but the Czechoslovak Olympic Committee would not allow her to do so.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Thereafter, as Olga Connolly, she took part in every Olympics until 1972 competing for the U.S.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] She was the flag bearer for the U.S. team at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The India men's national field hockey team won its sixth consecutive Olympic gold.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Despite the international tensions of 1956—or perhaps because of them—a young Melburnian, John Ian Wing, came up with a new idea for the closing ceremony.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Instead of marching as separate teams, behind their national flags, the athletes mingled together as they paraded into and around the arena for a final appearance before the spectators.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] It was the start of an Olympic tradition that has been followed ever since.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic flame was relayed to Melbourne after being lit at Olympia on 2 November 1956.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Greek runners took the flame from Olympia to Athens.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was then transferred to a miner's lamp, flown by a Qantas Super Constellation aircraft, "Southern Horizon" to Darwin, Northern Territory.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] A Royal Australian Air Force English Electric Canberra jet bomber transported the flame to Cairns, Queensland, where it arrived on 9 November 1956 and the Mayor of Cairns, Alderman W.J.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Fulton, lit the first torch with the torch design was identical to the one used for the 1948 London Games (except for the engraved city name and year).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The first runner was Con Verevis, a local man of Greek parentage.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was relayed down the east coast of Australia using die cast aluminium torches weighing about 3 pounds (1.8 kg).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The flame arrived in Melbourne on 22 November 1956, the day of the opening ceremony and The flame was lit at the Olympic stadium by Ron Clarke, who accidentally burned his arm in the process.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] While the Olympic flame was being carried to Sydney, an Australian veterinary student named Barry Larkin carried a fake Olympic Flame and fooled the mayor of Sydney.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The Melbourne Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival held in conjunction with the Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympics were first televised during the 1936 games to a domestic audience in Berlin.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Winter Olympics in Cortina d'Ampezzo were broadcast internationally with the organising committee giving the television rights gratis.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] While there was much interest in the games overseas, no international television or newsreel rights were awarded, as the Melbourne organising committee requested licensing payments for the broadcasting rights.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] However, domestic rights to the games were hastily agreed by the then three Melbourne stations, GTV9, HSV7 and ABV2, only a week before the opening ceremony.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The three Sydney stations, TCN9, ATN7 and ABN2, syndicated the Melbourne coverage.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Television in Australia was new, having its beginnings in September 1956.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] For many Australians, their first glimpse of television were Olympic broadcasts.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Around five thousand television sets were in Australia by the time of the Games, so the domestic audience largely watched the games at community halls and at Ampol petrol stations.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Summer Olympics featured 17 different sports encompassing 23 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 151 events (145 events in Melbourne and 6 equestrian events in Stockholm).
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] A total of 67 nations competed in the 1956 Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Eight countries made their Olympic debuts: Cambodia (only competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm), Ethiopia, Fiji, Kenya, Liberia, Malaya, North Borneo (modern-day Sabah of Malaysia), and Uganda.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would last until 1968.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] For the first time, the team of Republic of China effectively represented only Taiwan.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Five nations competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm, but did not attend the Games in Melbourne.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Cambodia, Egypt and Lebanon did not compete in Melbourne due to a boycott regarding the Suez Crisis, whilst the Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland all boycotted the Melbourne Olympics in protest at the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that returned to the games in this edition included Afghanistan and Colombia.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Helsinki 1952 but was absent in Melbourne 1956 included the People's Republic of China, Liechtenstein, Netherlands Antilles, and Saar.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] Bahamas, Bermuda, Fiji, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Kenya, Nigeria, Malaya, North Borneo, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, Uganda and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1956-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1956 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The **1964 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XVIII Olympiad** and commonly known as **Tokyo 1964**, were an international multi-sport event held from 10 to 24 October 1964 in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Tokyo had been awarded the organization of the 1940 Summer Olympics, but this honor was subsequently passed to Helsinki due to Japan's invasion of China, before ultimately being cancelled due to World War II.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The 1964 Summer Olympics in Tokyo were the first Olympic Games held in the city and, as of 2021, the only ones to have spectators, as the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo were conducted without spectators due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Tokyo was chosen as the host city during the 55th IOC Session in West Germany on 26 May 1959.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The 1964 Summer Games were the first Olympics held in Asia, and marked the first time South Africa was excluded for using its apartheid system in sports.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Until 1960, South Africa had fielded segregated teams, conforming to the country's racial classifications; for the 1964 Games the International Olympic Committee demanded a multi-racial delegation to be sent, and after South Africa refused, they were excluded from participating.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The country was, however, allowed to compete at the 1964 Summer Paralympics, also held in Tokyo, its Paralympic Games debut.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The 1964 Games were also the first to be telecast internationally without the need for tapes to be flown overseas, as they had been for the 1960 Olympics four years earlier.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The games were telecast to the United States using Syncom 3, the first geostationary communication satellite, and from there to Europe using Relay 1.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] These were also the first Olympic Games to have color telecasts, albeit partially.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Certain events such as the sumo wrestling and judo matches, sports popular in Japan, were tried out using Toshiba's new colour transmission system, but only for the domestic market.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The entire 1964 Olympic Games was chronicled in the ground-breaking 1965 sports documentary film *Tokyo Olympiad*, directed by Kon Ichikawa.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The games were scheduled for mid-October to avoid the city's midsummer heat and humidity and the September typhoon season.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The previous Olympics in Rome in 1960 started in late August and experienced hot weather.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The following games in 1968 in Mexico City also began in October.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The 1964 Olympics were also the last to use a traditional cinder track for the track events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Since 1968, a smooth, synthetic, all-weather track has been used.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The United States topped the gold medal table at these Games, while the Soviet Union won the most medals overall.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] In 2021, due to delay over the COVID-19 pandemic, Tokyo hosted the 2020 Summer Olympics, making it the first city in Asia to host the Summer Olympic Games twice.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Japan also hosted the Winter Olympics twice with the Sapporo 1972 and Nagano 1998 games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Tokyo won the rights to the Games on 26 May 1959 at the 55th IOC Session in Munich, West Germany, over bids from Detroit, Brussels and Vienna.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Toronto was an early bidder again in 1964 after the failed attempt for 1960 and failed to make the final round.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The 1964 Summer Olympics featured 19 different sports encompassing 25 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 163 events.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Note: In the Japan Olympic Committee report, sailing is listed as "yachting".
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Conventionally, countries are ranked by the number of gold medals they receive, followed then by the number of silver medals and, finally, bronze.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Ninety-four nations participated in the 1964 Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Cambodia returned to compete in Olympics after being absent in the 1960 Summer Olympics, but competed in all events despite having only competed in equestrian event in the 1956 Summer Olympics in Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Northern Rhodesia achieved full independence as Zambia on the same day as the closing ceremony.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Athletes from Southern Rhodesia competed under the banner of Rhodesia; this was the last of three appearances at the Summer Olympics by a Rhodesian representation.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Zimbabwe would later make its first appearance at the 1980 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany competed together as the United Team of Germany, as they had done previously in 1956 and 1960.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The nations would enter separate teams beginning with the 1968 Winter Olympics.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Indonesia was banned from the 1964 Olympics, due to its refusal to allow Israeli and Taiwanese athletes visas at the 1962 Asian Games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Indonesia was originally banned on the meeting which took place in Lausanne on 7 February 1963.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The decision was changed on 26 June 1964 citing the changed position of the Government of Indonesia towards the Tokyo games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] These games were the first to be telecast internationally.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The games were telecast to the United States using Syncom 3, the first geostationary communication satellite, and from there to Europe using Relay 1, an older satellite which allowed only 15–20 minutes of broadcast during each of its orbits.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Total broadcast time of programs delivered via satellite was 5 hours 41 minutes in the United States, 12 hours 27 minutes in Europe, and 14 hours 18 minutes in Canada.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Pictures were received via satellite in the United States, Canada, and 21 countries in Europe.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Several broadcasters recorded some sports from Japan and flown over to their countries.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] While the agreement to use satellite to transmit the games live to the United States was a proud achievement for the American government and Hughes Corporation which developed the satellites, NBC the rights holder had little interest in the project.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] NBC's participation was due to pressure from the Under-Secretary of State for Political Affairs Averell Harriman, and NBC intended to record the live transmissions for later use in sponsored shows.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] NBC broadcast the opening ceremonies live on the East coast of the United States, but delayed the broadcast on the West coast to 1:00 a.m. so Johnny Carson's *Tonight Show* would not be interrupted.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] When pressed on the issue NBC announced there would be no more live telecasts which angered the American State Department which saw the broadcasts as a matter of national prestige, and also the Hughes Aircraft Company who won the bid to build the satellite system over RCA which owned NBC.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] TRANSPAC-1, the first trans-Pacific communications cable from Japan to Hawaii was also finished in June 1964 in time for these games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Before this, most communications from Japan to other countries were via shortwave.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The start of operations for the first Japanese bullet train (the Tokaido Shinkansen) between Tokyo Station and Shin-Ōsaka Station was scheduled to coincide with the Olympic games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] The first regularly scheduled train ran on 1 October 1964, just nine days before the opening of the games, transporting passengers 515 kilometers (320 mi) in about four hours, and connecting the three major metropolitan areas of Tokyo, Nagoya, and Osaka.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Some already-planned upgrades to both highways and commuter rail lines were rescheduled for completion in time for these games.
[src:baseball-at-the-summer-olympics/1964-summer-olympics] Of the eight main expressways approved by the Tokyo Metropolitan Government in 1959, No.
